reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Valine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Valine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"Multiple convergent prebiotic pathways to valine (2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid) originating from CO\u2082 fixation in hydrothermal vents, proceeding through hub intermediates pyruvate and \u03b1-ketoisovalerate for reductive amination and transamination routes, and through isobutyraldehyde for Strecker synthesis routes on surfaces. The network leverages three environments: hydrothermal CO\u2082 reduction and carbon chain building on iron-sulfur minerals, surface Strecker synthesis and UV-driven chemistry, and biochemical transamination for final assembly. Key hubs are pyruvate, \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, isobutyraldehyde, CO, and NH\u2083, ensuring dense interconnection and redundancy across environments.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"dihydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Hydrogen gas\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"oxidane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon monoxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Carbon monoxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO/c1-2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHO2-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Pyruvate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8O4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxy-2-methyl-3-oxobutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Acetolactate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H8O4/c1-3(6)5(2,9)4(7)8/h9H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"\u03b1-Ketoisovalerate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H8O3/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-methylpropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H8O/c1-3(2)4-5/h3-4H,1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H10N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Valine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H10N2/c1-3(2)4(6)5-7/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H11NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Valine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H11NO2/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Alanine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO\u2082 reduction to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich fluids\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 is adsorbed on the greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084) surface, which acts as an analog of biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters. H\u2082 dissociatively adsorbs, providing hydride equivalents that reduce CO\u2082 to formate via surface-bound intermediates.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Demonstrated by Roldan et al. (2015) and Preiner et al. (2020). Greigite catalyzes CO\u2082 reduction to formate under simulated alkaline vent conditions. This is a cornerstone reaction of the iron-sulfur world hypothesis (W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1988). Herschy et al. (2014) showed formate production in alkaline vent simulators.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Reverse water-gas shift reaction to CO\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Black smoker or high-T hydrothermal conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 CO + H\u2082O on magnetite surfaces. The reaction proceeds via redox cycling of Fe\u00b2\u207a/Fe\u00b3\u207a in the magnetite lattice, facilitating oxygen transfer from CO\u2082.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The reverse water-gas shift on iron oxide catalysts is well-documented industrially and has been invoked in prebiotic contexts. Magnetite catalyzes this reaction efficiently at elevated temperatures (Shock & Schulte, 1998). CO is an essential C1 feedstock for Fischer-Tropsch and acetyl-CoA analog pathways.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of formaldehyde from CO\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Fischer-Tropsch conditions on mineral surfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO adsorbs on the magnetite/FeS surface and is partially hydrogenated by H\u2082 to yield formaldehyde (HCHO) as a C1 oxygenate product, an early step in the Fischer-Tropsch cascade.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"McCollom et al. (1999) and Rushdi & Simoneit (2001) demonstrated Fischer-Tropsch-type reactions under hydrothermal conditions producing a range of oxygenated C1-C4 compounds including formaldehyde and other aldehydes on iron oxide surfaces.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate reduction to formaldehyde on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-420K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Sequential reduction in hydrothermal gradient\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate is further reduced by H\u2082 on magnetite surfaces, losing one oxygen as water to yield formaldehyde. This proceeds through a surface formate intermediate that undergoes selective reduction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Preiner et al. (2020) showed stepwise reduction of CO\u2082 through formate to formaldehyde on native iron and magnetite surfaces. This sequential reduction pathway provides an alternative route to formaldehyde complementing direct Fischer-Tropsch synthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis via carbonylation on FeNiS\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\", \"awaruite (Ni\u2083Fe)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeNiS mixed catalyst (greigite + Ni phases)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline hydrothermal vent, acetyl-CoA pathway analog, pH gradient\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 is reduced to an activated C1 unit (CO/formyl), which combines with another CO on FeNiS surfaces to form an acetyl intermediate (analogous to acetyl-CoA pathway). Further carboxylation of acetyl yields pyruvate. The reaction proceeds: CO\u2082 \u2192 CO \u2192 CH\u2083CO-[surface] \u2192 CH\u2083COCOO\u207b (pyruvate) via sequential carbonyl insertion and carboxylation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Varma et al. (2018) demonstrated native iron-driven fixation of CO\u2082 to pyruvate and other \u03b1-keto acids under mild hydrothermal conditions. Cody et al. (2000) showed carbonylation reactions on FeNiS catalysts producing pyruvate from CO under hydrothermal conditions. Muchowska et al. (2017) demonstrated iron-promoted reductive tricarboxylic acid intermediates. This is a key step linking C1 fixation to central carbon metabolism.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate decarboxylation to acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Non-oxidative decarboxylation on mineral surface\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate undergoes thermal or mineral-catalyzed non-oxidative decarboxylation at the \u03b1-keto position, losing CO\u2082 to yield acetaldehyde. The pyrite surface stabilizes the transition state through coordination of the keto-acid moiety.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde is well-documented at elevated temperatures (Cooper et al., 2011). Under hydrothermal conditions, this reaction proceeds readily (t\u2081/\u2082 ~ hours at 350K). This connects central carbon metabolism to aldehyde chemistry critical for downstream condensations.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate condensation to acetolactate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\", \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite and iron-sulfur minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Thiamine-independent condensation analog; concentration by mineral adsorption\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Two pyruvate molecules undergo a thiamine-independent condensation reaction on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces. The first pyruvate is decarboxylated to generate a reactive acetaldehyde/hydroxyethyl equivalent, which attacks the second pyruvate at the carbonyl carbon, yielding acetolactate (2-hydroxy-2-methyl-3-oxobutanoate) and CO\u2082.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction is the prebiotic analog of acetolactate synthase in the biological valine biosynthesis pathway. W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1990) proposed that such condensation reactions could proceed on pyrite surfaces. Keller et al. (2014) demonstrated that many reactions of the modern TCA cycle and branched-chain amino acid pathways proceed non-enzymatically with iron-sulfur minerals. Acetolactate formation from pyruvate is the committed step toward branched-chain amino acid precursors.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetolactate decarboxylation and rearrangement to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\", \"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Thermal decarboxylation in warm evaporitic pool; may also proceed by UV-assisted decarboxylation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetolactate undergoes decarboxylation and 1,2-methyl shift (pinacol-type rearrangement) to yield 3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid (\u03b1-ketoisovalerate). The clay surface provides Lewis acid sites that facilitate the rearrangement, while UV on TiO\u2082 can assist the decarboxylation step. In biology, this is catalyzed by acetohydroxy acid isomeroreductase.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Non-enzymatic decarboxylation of acetolactate is spontaneous at mildly elevated temperatures (## Gollop et al., 1989). The rearrangement can also yield acetoin under some conditions, but at surface temperatures and slightly acidic conditions on clay, \u03b1-ketoisovalerate is a major product. Keller et al. (2014) observed non-enzymatic interconversions of TCA and amino acid precursors. This is the key branching point for valine biosynthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate to valine on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"NH\u2083-rich alkaline vent fluid, reducing conditions (H\u2082 excess)\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The \u03b1-keto group of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate reacts with ammonia to form an imine (Schiff base) intermediate, which is then reduced by H\u2082 on the greigite mineral surface acting as a hydrogenation catalyst, yielding valine. The FeS mineral provides the reducing equivalents analogous to NADH in biological transaminases.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003) demonstrated reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids on (Fe,Ni)S surfaces under simulated hydrothermal vent conditions. Wang et al. (2011) showed efficient reductive amination on iron-sulfur minerals. Barge et al. (2019) confirmed amino acid synthesis via reductive amination on iron oxyhydroxide precipitates. This is the most direct route to valine from its corresponding \u03b1-keto acid.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"420-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"High-temperature Fischer-Tropsch zone, branched products favored at higher T\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO and H\u2082 undergo Fischer-Tropsch-type polymerization on the magnetite surface. Chain growth proceeds via carbide or CO insertion mechanism, with branching favored at higher temperatures. Isobutyraldehyde (2-methylpropanal) is produced as one of the C4 branched oxygenate products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"McCollom et al. (1999) and Rushdi & Simoneit (2001) demonstrated that Fischer-Tropsch-type reactions under hydrothermal conditions on magnetite yield a distribution of linear and branched hydrocarbons and oxygenates including C3-C5 aldehydes. Branched products (including isobutyraldehyde) are observed as minor but significant products. This provides a direct abiotic source of the specific aldehyde needed for Strecker valine synthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Oxidative decarboxylation of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate to isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\", \"montmorillonite clay\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO\u2082 (photocatalyst)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation in shallow pool; photodecarboxylation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV photons absorbed by TiO\u2082 generate electron-hole pairs. The hole oxidizes the \u03b1-keto acid, driving decarboxylation to yield the aldehyde (isobutyraldehyde) and CO\u2082. This is analogous to the biological oxidative decarboxylation by \u03b1-ketoacid dehydrogenases.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Photooxidative decarboxylation of \u03b1-keto acids by UV/TiO\u2082 has been demonstrated (Kraeutler & Bard, 1978; Guzman & Martin, 2009). On early Earth with intense UV and no ozone layer, TiO\u2082 minerals (anatase, rutile) in shallow pools would drive this photochemistry efficiently. This connects the \u03b1-ketoisovalerate hub to the Strecker aldehyde route.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis step 1: aminonitrile formation from isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (concentrates reactants)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Evaporitic pool, concentrated reactants by clay adsorption\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Isobutyraldehyde reacts with ammonia to form an imine (Schiff base): (CH\u2083)\u2082CHCHO + NH\u2083 \u2192 (CH\u2083)\u2082CHCH=NH + H\u2082O. The imine is then attacked by cyanide (HCN) in a nucleophilic addition to yield the \u03b1-aminonitrile: (CH\u2083)\u2082CHCH=NH + HCN \u2192 (CH\u2083)\u2082CHCH(NH\u2082)CN (valine aminonitrile). Montmorillonite concentrates reactants by adsorption.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker synthesis is one of the oldest and most robust prebiotic amino acid syntheses (Strecker, 1850; Miller, 1953). It proceeds readily at ambient temperatures in aqueous solution. Isobutyraldehyde gives valine specifically. Montmorillonite clay enhances the reaction by concentrating aldehyde, NH\u2083, and HCN on its interlayer surfaces (Ferris et al., 1996; Rimola et al., 2007). This is a key surface-environment route to valine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis step 2: aminonitrile hydrolysis to valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"330-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (Lewis acid sites)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Warm evaporitic pool, mildly acidic to neutral pH; wet-dry cycling may assist\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The nitrile group of valine aminonitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis: -CN + H\u2082O \u2192 -C(=O)NH\u2082 (amide intermediate) \u2192 -COOH + NH\u2083. The overall reaction: (CH\u2083)\u2082CHCH(NH\u2082)CN + 2H\u2082O \u2192 (CH\u2083)\u2082CHCH(NH\u2082)COOH + NH\u2083. Clay Lewis acid sites catalyze the hydrolysis. Phosphate minerals buffer pH.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis to carboxylic acids is spontaneous under mildly acidic to neutral conditions and accelerated at elevated temperatures (Schlesinger & Miller, 1983). The Strecker route to amino acids via aminonitrile hydrolysis has been demonstrated for numerous amino acids including valine. Montmorillonite catalyzes nitrile hydrolysis through Lewis acid activation of the nitrile carbon (Ferris, 2005). NH\u2083 is regenerated, making it catalytic.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline vent conditions, NH\u2083-rich, H\u2082-rich\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate reacts with ammonia to form an imine intermediate (pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 \u03b1-iminopropanoate + H\u2082O), which is reduced by H\u2082 on greigite surfaces to yield alanine. Identical mechanism to rxn_009 but with the simpler C3 substrate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003) demonstrated reductive amination of pyruvate and other \u03b1-keto acids on (Fe,Ni)S surfaces. This reaction is a direct prebiotic analog of alanine aminotransferase. Alanine is one of the simplest and most abundant prebiotic amino acids. Required as amino group donor for the transamination route to valine (rxn_015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Transamination: \u03b1-ketoisovalerate + alanine \u2192 valine + pyruvate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyridoxal (or mineral-surface catalyzed)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Prebiotic pool with concentrated amino and keto acids; metal ion catalysis (Cu\u00b2\u207a, Fe\u00b2\u207a)\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Transamination proceeds via a Schiff base mechanism: alanine forms a Schiff base with a carbonyl catalyst (e.g., pyridoxal analog or mineral-bound aldehyde). Tautomerization shifts the amino group, producing pyruvate and the corresponding amino acid of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (valine). Metal ions (Fe\u00b2\u207a, Cu\u00b2\u207a) catalyze the tautomerization step.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Non-enzymatic transamination between amino acids and \u03b1-keto acids has been demonstrated under prebiotic conditions by Nakada & Weinhouse (1953) and more recently by Wachtershauser (1992). Copper(II) and iron(II) ions catalyze transamination effectively. Keller et al. (2014) showed non-enzymatic transamination reactions occurring with plausible prebiotic metal catalysts. This route regenerates pyruvate, creating a catalytic cycle.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Formaldehyde condensation with CO to glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde precursors\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-420K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mackinawite/magnetite mixed surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Carbon chain extension on mineral surfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde undergoes CO insertion/carbonylation on FeS surfaces to form glycolaldehyde (HOCH\u2082CHO) as a C2 building block. This proceeds via surface-bound formyl intermediate that couples with formaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Preiner et al. (2020) showed progressive carbon fixation from C1 to C2 compounds on native iron surfaces. Glycolaldehyde formation from formaldehyde in the formose reaction context and through carbonylation on mineral surfaces has been described. Glycolaldehyde is an important prebiotic C2 aldehyde building block (Breslow, 1959).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker synthesis of alanine from acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Evaporitic pool; Strecker conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetaldehyde reacts with ammonia to form ethylideneamine (CH\u2083CH=NH), which is then attacked by HCN to form \u03b1-aminopropionitrile (alanine aminonitrile). Hydrolysis yields alanine + NH\u2083. Presented as one-pot Strecker synthesis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Strecker synthesis of alanine from acetaldehyde is one of the most commonly demonstrated prebiotic amino acid syntheses (Miller, 1953; Schlesinger & Miller, 1983). Acetaldehyde is the simplest substrate yielding a chiral amino acid. This provides a surface-environment route to alanine complementing the hydrothermal reductive amination route (rxn_014), which then feeds into the transamination pathway (rxn_015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"UV-driven formaldehyde-based pyruvate synthesis on TiO\u2082\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\", \"phosphate minerals (struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO\u2082 (photocatalyst)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (\u03bb < 300 nm), shallow geothermal pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde undergoes UV-driven photoredox condensation in the presence of CO\u2082 on TiO\u2082 surfaces. Sequential aldol condensations and photooxidation steps convert 3 HCHO into pyruvate via glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde intermediates, with CO\u2082 providing additional carboxylation. TiO\u2082 provides photogenerated oxidants.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Guzman & Martin (2009) demonstrated UV/TiO\u2082-driven production of pyruvate and other \u03b1-keto acids from simple aldehydes. Ritson & Sutherland (2012) showed UV-driven interconversions of C2-C3 intermediates. This provides an independent surface-environment route to pyruvate, creating convergence with the hydrothermal route (rxn_005), ensuring the pyruvate hub is fed from multiple environments.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation \u2192 pyruvate \u2192 acetolactate \u2192 reductive amination to valine\",\n      \"description\": \"Complete hydrothermal pathway from CO\u2082 through the acetyl-CoA analog to pyruvate, then pyruvate self-condensation to acetolactate, rearrangement to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, and reductive amination to valine. Analogous to the biological branched-chain amino acid biosynthesis pathway.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 pyruvate \u2192 acetolactate \u2192 reductive amination\",\n      \"description\": \"Stepwise CO\u2082 reduction through formate and formaldehyde intermediates to pyruvate, then via acetolactate to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate and reductive amination to valine. Emphasizes the sequential reduction pathway.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch isobutyraldehyde \u2192 Strecker synthesis to valine\",\n      \"description\": \"CO produced hydrothermally undergoes Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis to directly produce isobutyraldehyde, which is then subjected to Strecker synthesis on surfaces with HCN and NH\u2083 to yield valine via the aminonitrile intermediate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate \u2192 surface decarboxylation \u2192 Strecker\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate from hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation is condensed to acetolactate and rearranged to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, which is photodecarboxylated on TiO\u2082 surfaces to isobutyraldehyde, then Strecker synthesis yields valine. This pathway crosses from hydrothermal to surface environments.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Transamination route: hydrothermal alanine + \u03b1-ketoisovalerate \u2192 valine\",\n      \"description\": \"Alanine is synthesized via reductive amination of pyruvate in hydrothermal vents. Separately, \u03b1-ketoisovalerate is produced via pyruvate condensation. These combine in a biochemical transamination reaction to yield valine and regenerate pyruvate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Transamination with surface-derived alanine (Strecker) + hydrothermal \u03b1-ketoisovalerate\",\n      \"description\": \"Alanine is produced on the surface via Strecker synthesis from acetaldehyde, while \u03b1-ketoisovalerate comes from the hydrothermal pyruvate condensation pathway. The two meet in a biochemical transamination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"CO route \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 surface pyruvate \u2192 acetolactate \u2192 reductive amination\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082 is converted to CO hydrothermally, then to formaldehyde via Fischer-Tropsch, formaldehyde is transported to surfaces where UV/TiO\u2082 drives pyruvate synthesis, then proceeds through acetolactate to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate and back to hydrothermal vents for reductive amination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 Fischer-Tropsch aldehyde \u2192 Strecker\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082 is first reduced to formate, then to formaldehyde hydrothermally. Separately, CO from reverse water-gas shift drives Fischer-Tropsch synthesis of isobutyraldehyde. Both C1 fixation pathways converge at the Strecker synthesis on surfaces.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface photochemical pyruvate \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate \u2192 direct reductive amination\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde from hydrothermal sources is photochemically converted to pyruvate on TiO\u2082 surfaces, condensed to acetolactate, rearranged to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate on surface clays, then reductively aminated to valine using hydrothermal H\u2082 and NH\u2083.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Full cross-environment cycle: hydrothermal pyruvate \u2192 surface Strecker aldehyde \u2192 valine with pyruvate regeneration\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate from hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation undergoes condensation to acetolactate and rearrangement to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate. \u03b1-Ketoisovalerate is photodecarboxylated on surfaces to isobutyraldehyde. Strecker synthesis yields valine. Separately, transamination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate with alanine yields valine and regenerates pyruvate, closing a catalytic cycle. This pathway demonstrates the full environmental interconnection and pyruvate regeneration.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_006\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate - central metabolic hub fed by hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation and surface photochemistry, consumed by condensation, decarboxylation, and reductive amination pathways\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"description\": \"\u03b1-Ketoisovalerate - key branching hub connecting the acetolactate pathway to three distinct routes to valine: reductive amination, photodecarboxylation to Strecker aldehyde, and transamination\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"description\": \"Isobutyraldehyde - aldehyde hub connecting Fischer-Tropsch synthesis and \u03b1-ketoisovalerate decarboxylation to the Strecker amino acid synthesis pathway\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"description\": \"Ammonia - nitrogen source hub consumed in reductive amination and Strecker synthesis, regenerated in nitrile hydrolysis and transamination\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"description\": \"Carbon monoxide - C1 hub connecting reverse water-gas shift to Fischer-Tropsch synthesis and pyruvate carbonylation pathways\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_016\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Valine", "overall_strategy": "Multiple convergent prebiotic pathways to valine (2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid) originating from CO\u2082 fixation in hydrothermal vents, proceeding through hub intermediates pyruvate and \u03b1-ketoisovalerate for reductive amination and transamination routes, and through isobutyraldehyde for Strecker synthesis routes on surfaces. The network leverages three environments: hydrothermal CO\u2082 reduction and carbon chain building on iron-sulfur minerals, surface Strecker synthesis and UV-driven chemistry, and biochemical transamination for final assembly. Key hubs are pyruvate, \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, isobutyraldehyde, CO, and NH\u2083, ensuring dense interconnection and redundancy across environments.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "Carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "dihydrogen", "common_name": "Hydrogen gas", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "Ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "formonitrile", "common_name": "Hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "oxidane", "common_name": "Water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CO", "iupac_name": "carbon monoxide", "common_name": "Carbon monoxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO/c1-2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CHO2-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "Formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "Formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "Pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "acetaldehyde", "common_name": "Acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C5H8O4", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxy-2-methyl-3-oxobutanoic acid", "common_name": "Acetolactate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H8O4/c1-3(6)5(2,9)4(7)8/h9H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C5H8O3", "iupac_name": "3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid", "common_name": "\u03b1-Ketoisovalerate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H8O3/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C4H8O", "iupac_name": "2-methylpropanal", "common_name": "Isobutyraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8O/c1-3(2)4-5/h3-4H,1-2H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C5H10N2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile", "common_name": "Valine aminonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H10N2/c1-3(2)4(6)5-7/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C5H11NO2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid", "common_name": "Valine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H11NO2/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "Alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "glycolaldehyde", "common_name": "Glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO\u2082 reduction to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich fluids"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 is adsorbed on the greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084) surface, which acts as an analog of biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters. H\u2082 dissociatively adsorbs, providing hydride equivalents that reduce CO\u2082 to formate via surface-bound intermediates.", "reasoning": "Demonstrated by Roldan et al. (2015) and Preiner et al. (2020). Greigite catalyzes CO\u2082 reduction to formate under simulated alkaline vent conditions. This is a cornerstone reaction of the iron-sulfur world hypothesis (W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1988). Herschy et al. (2014) showed formate production in alkaline vent simulators."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Reverse water-gas shift reaction to CO", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006", "mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Black smoker or high-T hydrothermal conditions"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 CO + H\u2082O on magnetite surfaces. The reaction proceeds via redox cycling of Fe\u00b2\u207a/Fe\u00b3\u207a in the magnetite lattice, facilitating oxygen transfer from CO\u2082.", "reasoning": "The reverse water-gas shift on iron oxide catalysts is well-documented industrially and has been invoked in prebiotic contexts. Magnetite catalyzes this reaction efficiently at elevated temperatures (Shock & Schulte, 1998). CO is an essential C1 feedstock for Fischer-Tropsch and acetyl-CoA analog pathways."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of formaldehyde from CO", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Fischer-Tropsch conditions on mineral surfaces"}, "mechanism": "CO adsorbs on the magnetite/FeS surface and is partially hydrogenated by H\u2082 to yield formaldehyde (HCHO) as a C1 oxygenate product, an early step in the Fischer-Tropsch cascade.", "reasoning": "McCollom et al. (1999) and Rushdi & Simoneit (2001) demonstrated Fischer-Tropsch-type reactions under hydrothermal conditions producing a range of oxygenated C1-C4 compounds including formaldehyde and other aldehydes on iron oxide surfaces."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Formate reduction to formaldehyde on magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008", "mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-420K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Sequential reduction in hydrothermal gradient"}, "mechanism": "Formate is further reduced by H\u2082 on magnetite surfaces, losing one oxygen as water to yield formaldehyde. This proceeds through a surface formate intermediate that undergoes selective reduction.", "reasoning": "Preiner et al. (2020) showed stepwise reduction of CO\u2082 through formate to formaldehyde on native iron and magnetite surfaces. This sequential reduction pathway provides an alternative route to formaldehyde complementing direct Fischer-Tropsch synthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis via carbonylation on FeNiS", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_006", "mol_002", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "awaruite (Ni\u2083Fe)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (100 bar)", "catalyst": "FeNiS mixed catalyst (greigite + Ni phases)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline hydrothermal vent, acetyl-CoA pathway analog, pH gradient"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 is reduced to an activated C1 unit (CO/formyl), which combines with another CO on FeNiS surfaces to form an acetyl intermediate (analogous to acetyl-CoA pathway). Further carboxylation of acetyl yields pyruvate. The reaction proceeds: CO\u2082 \u2192 CO \u2192 CH\u2083CO-[surface] \u2192 CH\u2083COCOO\u207b (pyruvate) via sequential carbonyl insertion and carboxylation.", "reasoning": "Varma et al. (2018) demonstrated native iron-driven fixation of CO\u2082 to pyruvate and other \u03b1-keto acids under mild hydrothermal conditions. Cody et al. (2000) showed carbonylation reactions on FeNiS catalysts producing pyruvate from CO under hydrothermal conditions. Muchowska et al. (2017) demonstrated iron-promoted reductive tricarboxylic acid intermediates. This is a key step linking C1 fixation to central carbon metabolism."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Pyruvate decarboxylation to acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010", "mol_001"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS\u2082)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite (FeS\u2082)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Non-oxidative decarboxylation on mineral surface"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate undergoes thermal or mineral-catalyzed non-oxidative decarboxylation at the \u03b1-keto position, losing CO\u2082 to yield acetaldehyde. The pyrite surface stabilizes the transition state through coordination of the keto-acid moiety.", "reasoning": "Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde is well-documented at elevated temperatures (Cooper et al., 2011). Under hydrothermal conditions, this reaction proceeds readily (t\u2081/\u2082 ~ hours at 350K). This connects central carbon metabolism to aldehyde chemistry critical for downstream condensations."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Pyruvate condensation to acetolactate", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_011", "mol_001"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS\u2082)", "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "pyrite and iron-sulfur minerals", "aqueous": true, "other": "Thiamine-independent condensation analog; concentration by mineral adsorption"}, "mechanism": "Two pyruvate molecules undergo a thiamine-independent condensation reaction on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces. The first pyruvate is decarboxylated to generate a reactive acetaldehyde/hydroxyethyl equivalent, which attacks the second pyruvate at the carbonyl carbon, yielding acetolactate (2-hydroxy-2-methyl-3-oxobutanoate) and CO\u2082.", "reasoning": "This reaction is the prebiotic analog of acetolactate synthase in the biological valine biosynthesis pathway. W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1990) proposed that such condensation reactions could proceed on pyrite surfaces. Keller et al. (2014) demonstrated that many reactions of the modern TCA cycle and branched-chain amino acid pathways proceed non-enzymatically with iron-sulfur minerals. Acetolactate formation from pyruvate is the committed step toward branched-chain amino acid precursors."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Acetolactate decarboxylation and rearrangement to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate", "inputs": ["mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_012", "mol_001"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay", "TiO\u2082 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "Thermal decarboxylation in warm evaporitic pool; may also proceed by UV-assisted decarboxylation"}, "mechanism": "Acetolactate undergoes decarboxylation and 1,2-methyl shift (pinacol-type rearrangement) to yield 3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid (\u03b1-ketoisovalerate). The clay surface provides Lewis acid sites that facilitate the rearrangement, while UV on TiO\u2082 can assist the decarboxylation step. In biology, this is catalyzed by acetohydroxy acid isomeroreductase.", "reasoning": "Non-enzymatic decarboxylation of acetolactate is spontaneous at mildly elevated temperatures (## Gollop et al., 1989). The rearrangement can also yield acetoin under some conditions, but at surface temperatures and slightly acidic conditions on clay, \u03b1-ketoisovalerate is a major product. Keller et al. (2014) observed non-enzymatic interconversions of TCA and amino acid precursors. This is the key branching point for valine biosynthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate to valine on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_015", "mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "NH\u2083-rich alkaline vent fluid, reducing conditions (H\u2082 excess)"}, "mechanism": "The \u03b1-keto group of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate reacts with ammonia to form an imine (Schiff base) intermediate, which is then reduced by H\u2082 on the greigite mineral surface acting as a hydrogenation catalyst, yielding valine. The FeS mineral provides the reducing equivalents analogous to NADH in biological transaminases.", "reasoning": "Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003) demonstrated reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids on (Fe,Ni)S surfaces under simulated hydrothermal vent conditions. Wang et al. (2011) showed efficient reductive amination on iron-sulfur minerals. Barge et al. (2019) confirmed amino acid synthesis via reductive amination on iron oxyhydroxide precipitates. This is the most direct route to valine from its corresponding \u03b1-keto acid."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of isobutyraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "420-500K", "pressure": "high (100-200 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "High-temperature Fischer-Tropsch zone, branched products favored at higher T"}, "mechanism": "CO and H\u2082 undergo Fischer-Tropsch-type polymerization on the magnetite surface. Chain growth proceeds via carbide or CO insertion mechanism, with branching favored at higher temperatures. Isobutyraldehyde (2-methylpropanal) is produced as one of the C4 branched oxygenate products.", "reasoning": "McCollom et al. (1999) and Rushdi & Simoneit (2001) demonstrated that Fischer-Tropsch-type reactions under hydrothermal conditions on magnetite yield a distribution of linear and branched hydrocarbons and oxygenates including C3-C5 aldehydes. Branched products (including isobutyraldehyde) are observed as minor but significant products. This provides a direct abiotic source of the specific aldehyde needed for Strecker valine synthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Oxidative decarboxylation of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate to isobutyraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_013", "mol_001"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO\u2082 (anatase)", "montmorillonite clay"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO\u2082 (photocatalyst)", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation in shallow pool; photodecarboxylation"}, "mechanism": "UV photons absorbed by TiO\u2082 generate electron-hole pairs. The hole oxidizes the \u03b1-keto acid, driving decarboxylation to yield the aldehyde (isobutyraldehyde) and CO\u2082. This is analogous to the biological oxidative decarboxylation by \u03b1-ketoacid dehydrogenases.", "reasoning": "Photooxidative decarboxylation of \u03b1-keto acids by UV/TiO\u2082 has been demonstrated (Kraeutler & Bard, 1978; Guzman & Martin, 2009). On early Earth with intense UV and no ozone layer, TiO\u2082 minerals (anatase, rutile) in shallow pools would drive this photochemistry efficiently. This connects the \u03b1-ketoisovalerate hub to the Strecker aldehyde route."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Strecker synthesis step 1: aminonitrile formation from isobutyraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (concentrates reactants)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Evaporitic pool, concentrated reactants by clay adsorption"}, "mechanism": "Isobutyraldehyde reacts with ammonia to form an imine (Schiff base): (CH\u2083)\u2082CHCHO + NH\u2083 \u2192 (CH\u2083)\u2082CHCH=NH + H\u2082O. The imine is then attacked by cyanide (HCN) in a nucleophilic addition to yield the \u03b1-aminonitrile: (CH\u2083)\u2082CHCH=NH + HCN \u2192 (CH\u2083)\u2082CHCH(NH\u2082)CN (valine aminonitrile). Montmorillonite concentrates reactants by adsorption.", "reasoning": "The Strecker synthesis is one of the oldest and most robust prebiotic amino acid syntheses (Strecker, 1850; Miller, 1953). It proceeds readily at ambient temperatures in aqueous solution. Isobutyraldehyde gives valine specifically. Montmorillonite clay enhances the reaction by concentrating aldehyde, NH\u2083, and HCN on its interlayer surfaces (Ferris et al., 1996; Rimola et al., 2007). This is a key surface-environment route to valine."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Strecker synthesis step 2: aminonitrile hydrolysis to valine", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_015", "mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "330-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (Lewis acid sites)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Warm evaporitic pool, mildly acidic to neutral pH; wet-dry cycling may assist"}, "mechanism": "The nitrile group of valine aminonitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis: -CN + H\u2082O \u2192 -C(=O)NH\u2082 (amide intermediate) \u2192 -COOH + NH\u2083. The overall reaction: (CH\u2083)\u2082CHCH(NH\u2082)CN + 2H\u2082O \u2192 (CH\u2083)\u2082CHCH(NH\u2082)COOH + NH\u2083. Clay Lewis acid sites catalyze the hydrolysis. Phosphate minerals buffer pH.", "reasoning": "Nitrile hydrolysis to carboxylic acids is spontaneous under mildly acidic to neutral conditions and accelerated at elevated temperatures (Schlesinger & Miller, 1983). The Strecker route to amino acids via aminonitrile hydrolysis has been demonstrated for numerous amino acids including valine. Montmorillonite catalyzes nitrile hydrolysis through Lewis acid activation of the nitrile carbon (Ferris, 2005). NH\u2083 is regenerated, making it catalytic."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_016", "mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline vent conditions, NH\u2083-rich, H\u2082-rich"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate reacts with ammonia to form an imine intermediate (pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 \u03b1-iminopropanoate + H\u2082O), which is reduced by H\u2082 on greigite surfaces to yield alanine. Identical mechanism to rxn_009 but with the simpler C3 substrate.", "reasoning": "Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003) demonstrated reductive amination of pyruvate and other \u03b1-keto acids on (Fe,Ni)S surfaces. This reaction is a direct prebiotic analog of alanine aminotransferase. Alanine is one of the simplest and most abundant prebiotic amino acids. Required as amino group donor for the transamination route to valine (rxn_015)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Transamination: \u03b1-ketoisovalerate + alanine \u2192 valine + pyruvate", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_016"], "outputs": ["mol_015", "mol_009"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "pyridoxal (or mineral-surface catalyzed)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Prebiotic pool with concentrated amino and keto acids; metal ion catalysis (Cu\u00b2\u207a, Fe\u00b2\u207a)"}, "mechanism": "Transamination proceeds via a Schiff base mechanism: alanine forms a Schiff base with a carbonyl catalyst (e.g., pyridoxal analog or mineral-bound aldehyde). Tautomerization shifts the amino group, producing pyruvate and the corresponding amino acid of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (valine). Metal ions (Fe\u00b2\u207a, Cu\u00b2\u207a) catalyze the tautomerization step.", "reasoning": "Non-enzymatic transamination between amino acids and \u03b1-keto acids has been demonstrated under prebiotic conditions by Nakada & Weinhouse (1953) and more recently by Wachtershauser (1992). Copper(II) and iron(II) ions catalyze transamination effectively. Keller et al. (2014) showed non-enzymatic transamination reactions occurring with plausible prebiotic metal catalysts. This route regenerates pyruvate, creating a catalytic cycle."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Formaldehyde condensation with CO to glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde precursors", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_006", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-420K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "mackinawite/magnetite mixed surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "Carbon chain extension on mineral surfaces"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde undergoes CO insertion/carbonylation on FeS surfaces to form glycolaldehyde (HOCH\u2082CHO) as a C2 building block. This proceeds via surface-bound formyl intermediate that couples with formaldehyde.", "reasoning": "Preiner et al. (2020) showed progressive carbon fixation from C1 to C2 compounds on native iron surfaces. Glycolaldehyde formation from formaldehyde in the formose reaction context and through carbonylation on mineral surfaces has been described. Glycolaldehyde is an important prebiotic C2 aldehyde building block (Breslow, 1959)."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Surface Strecker synthesis of alanine from acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_004", "mol_003", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay", "aqueous": true, "other": "Evaporitic pool; Strecker conditions"}, "mechanism": "Acetaldehyde reacts with ammonia to form ethylideneamine (CH\u2083CH=NH), which is then attacked by HCN to form \u03b1-aminopropionitrile (alanine aminonitrile). Hydrolysis yields alanine + NH\u2083. Presented as one-pot Strecker synthesis.", "reasoning": "Strecker synthesis of alanine from acetaldehyde is one of the most commonly demonstrated prebiotic amino acid syntheses (Miller, 1953; Schlesinger & Miller, 1983). Acetaldehyde is the simplest substrate yielding a chiral amino acid. This provides a surface-environment route to alanine complementing the hydrothermal reductive amination route (rxn_014), which then feeds into the transamination pathway (rxn_015)."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "UV-driven formaldehyde-based pyruvate synthesis on TiO\u2082", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_001", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO\u2082 (anatase)", "phosphate minerals (struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO\u2082 (photocatalyst)", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation (\u03bb < 300 nm), shallow geothermal pool"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde undergoes UV-driven photoredox condensation in the presence of CO\u2082 on TiO\u2082 surfaces. Sequential aldol condensations and photooxidation steps convert 3 HCHO into pyruvate via glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde intermediates, with CO\u2082 providing additional carboxylation. TiO\u2082 provides photogenerated oxidants.", "reasoning": "Guzman & Martin (2009) demonstrated UV/TiO\u2082-driven production of pyruvate and other \u03b1-keto acids from simple aldehydes. Ritson & Sutherland (2012) showed UV-driven interconversions of C2-C3 intermediates. This provides an independent surface-environment route to pyruvate, creating convergence with the hydrothermal route (rxn_005), ensuring the pyruvate hub is fed from multiple environments."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation \u2192 pyruvate \u2192 acetolactate \u2192 reductive amination to valine", "descripti