erent and environmentally progressive pathway to valine, even if some individual steps carry uncertainty.\n- Issues: ['Direct route through the biosynthetic-like acetolactate pathway. The pyruvate condensation to acetolactate (rxn_007) without thiamine is prebiotically uncertain, and the acetolactate-to-\u03b1-ketoisovalerate step (rxn_008) compresses a complex multi-step biological transformation (reduction, isomerization, dehydration) into a single surface reaction. Environmental flow is slightly awkward: Hydrothermal \u2192 Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Hydrothermal.', 'Longest route to valine through formate and formaldehyde. The UV-driven formaldehyde-to-pyruvate step (rxn_018) on TiO\u2082 is interesting but not strongly supported experimentally. Carries the same acetolactate pathway weakness as P1. Environmental flow oscillates: Hydrothermal \u2192 Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Hydrothermal.', 'Elegant short pathway through Fischer-Tropsch isobutyraldehyde and Strecker synthesis. The main weakness is the selectivity of FTT for branched C\u2084 aldehyde (rxn_010); FTT typically produces linear alkanes/alcohols and the branched aldehyde yield would be very low. The Strecker portion is well-established. Good environmental flow: Hydrothermal \u2192 Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Surface.', 'Convergent pathway requiring both \u03b1-ketoisovalerate and alanine. Transamination (rxn_015) is plausible with metal ion catalysis (Cu\u00b2\u207a, Fe\u00b2\u207a) but less efficient without pyridoxal phosphate. The convergent topology is a strength, and pyruvate regeneration creates a catalytic cycle. Same acetolactate bottleneck persists. Environmental flow: Hydrothermal \u2192 Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface + Hydrothermal \u2192 Biochemical.', 'Cross-environment pathway using surface Strecker alanine with hydrothermal \u03b1-ketoisovalerate for transamination. The acetaldehyde Strecker route to alanine (rxn_017) is well-supported (Miller-type). Convergent design is a strength but carries cumulative uncertainty from both acetolactate and transamination steps.', 'CO-based route through formaldehyde and UV-pyruvate synthesis. Multiple weakly supported steps accumulate uncertainty. The FTT formaldehyde synthesis (rxn_003) gives low yields, and the photochemical pyruvate synthesis (rxn_018) needs stronger support. Environmental oscillation reduces coherence.', 'Route from formate through formaldehyde to FTT isobutyraldehyde then Strecker. The connection between formaldehyde and isobutyraldehyde via FTT (rxn_010) is mechanistically unclear since rxn_010 uses CO+H\u2082 not formaldehyde. The pathway description appears inconsistent with the actual reaction substrates.', 'Surface-initiated route starting from photochemical pyruvate. Requires a formaldehyde source (additional upstream steps needed). Carries the acetolactate weakness. Reductive amination at the end requires return to hydrothermal conditions. The photochemical entry point is interesting but weakly supported.', 'Most comprehensive cross-environment pathway incorporating pyruvate regeneration cycle. Demonstrates the full network topology with Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow and pyruvate recycling. The catalytic cycle aspect (pyruvate consumed and regenerated) is a strength for sustained prebiotic production. Longest path with most accumulated uncertainty but showcases network connectivity.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "", "parsed_response": null, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 4409.907817840576, "success": false, "error_message": "{'type': 'error', 'error': {'details': None, 'type': 'overloaded_error', 'message': 'Overloaded'}, 'request_id': 'req_011CZ8S1t7XpVK81x9UYrn3x'}"}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-17T05:42:55.971726", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Valine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.8\n- Feedback: This is a well-designed and comprehensive prebiotic synthesis network for valine with strong topological properties. The network features 17 molecules, 18 reactions, 10 pathways, and 5 convergence points, demonstrating excellent redundancy and interconnection. Key strengths: (1) Hub molecules are well-chosen with pyruvate, \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, CO, and NH\u2083 serving as proper high-connectivity nodes; (2) Multiple routes to the target provide robustness; (3) Environmental flow is generally well-managed with clear Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical progression; (4) The Strecker synthesis portions are well-established chemistry; (5) Mineral catalysts are specified for hydrothermal reactions. Key weaknesses: (1) The acetolactate pathway (rxn_007 \u2192 rxn_008) is the critical bottleneck\u2014abiotic pyruvate condensation to acetolactate without thiamine and the subsequent complex rearrangement to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate are the least supported steps; (2) HCN (mol_004) is used as a reactant in Strecker reactions but has no production reaction in the network\u2014it should either be designated as a starting material or given a synthesis reaction (e.g., from NH\u2083 + CH\u2082O or spark discharge); (3) Fischer-Tropsch selectivity for branched isobutyraldehyde (rxn_010) is not well-justified. The network achieves a passing confidence of 0.80 primarily because the diversity of routes ensures that at least P4 (through Strecker synthesis) provides a chemically coherent and environmentally progressive pathway to valine, even if some individual steps carry uncertainty.\n- Issues: ['Direct route through the biosynthetic-like acetolactate pathway. The pyruvate condensation to acetolactate (rxn_007) without thiamine is prebiotically uncertain, and the acetolactate-to-\u03b1-ketoisovalerate step (rxn_008) compresses a complex multi-step biological transformation (reduction, isomerization, dehydration) into a single surface reaction. Environmental flow is slightly awkward: Hydrothermal \u2192 Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Hydrothermal.', 'Longest route to valine through formate and formaldehyde. The UV-driven formaldehyde-to-pyruvate step (rxn_018) on TiO\u2082 is interesting but not strongly supported experimentally. Carries the same acetolactate pathway weakness as P1. Environmental flow oscillates: Hydrothermal \u2192 Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Hydrothermal.', 'Elegant short pathway through Fischer-Tropsch isobutyraldehyde and Strecker synthesis. The main weakness is the selectivity of FTT for branched C\u2084 aldehyde (rxn_010); FTT typically produces linear alkanes/alcohols and the branched aldehyde yield would be very low. The Strecker portion is well-established. Good environmental flow: Hydrothermal \u2192 Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Surface.', 'Convergent pathway requiring both \u03b1-ketoisovalerate and alanine. Transamination (rxn_015) is plausible with metal ion catalysis (Cu\u00b2\u207a, Fe\u00b2\u207a) but less efficient without pyridoxal phosphate. The convergent topology is a strength, and pyruvate regeneration creates a catalytic cycle. Same acetolactate bottleneck persists. Environmental flow: Hydrothermal \u2192 Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface + Hydrothermal \u2192 Biochemical.', 'Cross-environment pathway using surface Strecker alanine with hydrothermal \u03b1-ketoisovalerate for transamination. The acetaldehyde Strecker route to alanine (rxn_017) is well-supported (Miller-type). Convergent design is a strength but carries cumulative uncertainty from both acetolactate and transamination steps.', 'CO-based route through formaldehyde and UV-pyruvate synthesis. Multiple weakly supported steps accumulate uncertainty. The FTT formaldehyde synthesis (rxn_003) gives low yields, and the photochemical pyruvate synthesis (rxn_018) needs stronger support. Environmental oscillation reduces coherence.', 'Route from formate through formaldehyde to FTT isobutyraldehyde then Strecker. The connection between formaldehyde and isobutyraldehyde via FTT (rxn_010) is mechanistically unclear since rxn_010 uses CO+H\u2082 not formaldehyde. The pathway description appears inconsistent with the actual reaction substrates.', 'Surface-initiated route starting from photochemical pyruvate. Requires a formaldehyde source (additional upstream steps needed). Carries the acetolactate weakness. Reductive amination at the end requires return to hydrothermal conditions. The photochemical entry point is interesting but weakly supported.', 'Most comprehensive cross-environment pathway incorporating pyruvate regeneration cycle. Demonstrates the full network topology with Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow and pyruvate recycling. The catalytic cycle aspect (pyruvate consumed and regenerated) is a strength for sustained prebiotic production. Longest path with most accumulated uncertainty but showcases network connectivity.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "", "parsed_response": null, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 102129.18305397034, "success": false, "error_message": "{'type': 'error', 'error': {'details': None, 'type': 'api_error', 'message': 'Internal server error'}, 'request_id': 'req_011CZ8SB43aHgWMEcmg8sj3c'}"}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-17T05:46:38.111853", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Valine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.8\n- Feedback: This is a well-designed and comprehensive prebiotic synthesis network for valine with strong topological properties. The network features 17 molecules, 18 reactions, 10 pathways, and 5 convergence points, demonstrating excellent redundancy and interconnection. Key strengths: (1) Hub molecules are well-chosen with pyruvate, \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, CO, and NH\u2083 serving as proper high-connectivity nodes; (2) Multiple routes to the target provide robustness; (3) Environmental flow is generally well-managed with clear Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical progression; (4) The Strecker synthesis portions are well-established chemistry; (5) Mineral catalysts are specified for hydrothermal reactions. Key weaknesses: (1) The acetolactate pathway (rxn_007 \u2192 rxn_008) is the critical bottleneck\u2014abiotic pyruvate condensation to acetolactate without thiamine and the subsequent complex rearrangement to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate are the least supported steps; (2) HCN (mol_004) is used as a reactant in Strecker reactions but has no production reaction in the network\u2014it should either be designated as a starting material or given a synthesis reaction (e.g., from NH\u2083 + CH\u2082O or spark discharge); (3) Fischer-Tropsch selectivity for branched isobutyraldehyde (rxn_010) is not well-justified. The network achieves a passing confidence of 0.80 primarily because the diversity of routes ensures that at least P4 (through Strecker synthesis) provides a chemically coherent and environmentally progressive pathway to valine, even if some individual steps carry uncertainty.\n- Issues: ['Direct route through the biosynthetic-like acetolactate pathway. The pyruvate condensation to acetolactate (rxn_007) without thiamine is prebiotically uncertain, and the acetolactate-to-\u03b1-ketoisovalerate step (rxn_008) compresses a complex multi-step biological transformation (reduction, isomerization, dehydration) into a single surface reaction. Environmental flow is slightly awkward: Hydrothermal \u2192 Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Hydrothermal.', 'Longest route to valine through formate and formaldehyde. The UV-driven formaldehyde-to-pyruvate step (rxn_018) on TiO\u2082 is interesting but not strongly supported experimentally. Carries the same acetolactate pathway weakness as P1. Environmental flow oscillates: Hydrothermal \u2192 Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Hydrothermal.', 'Elegant short pathway through Fischer-Tropsch isobutyraldehyde and Strecker synthesis. The main weakness is the selectivity of FTT for branched C\u2084 aldehyde (rxn_010); FTT typically produces linear alkanes/alcohols and the branched aldehyde yield would be very low. The Strecker portion is well-established. Good environmental flow: Hydrothermal \u2192 Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Surface.', 'Convergent pathway requiring both \u03b1-ketoisovalerate and alanine. Transamination (rxn_015) is plausible with metal ion catalysis (Cu\u00b2\u207a, Fe\u00b2\u207a) but less efficient without pyridoxal phosphate. The convergent topology is a strength, and pyruvate regeneration creates a catalytic cycle. Same acetolactate bottleneck persists. Environmental flow: Hydrothermal \u2192 Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface + Hydrothermal \u2192 Biochemical.', 'Cross-environment pathway using surface Strecker alanine with hydrothermal \u03b1-ketoisovalerate for transamination. The acetaldehyde Strecker route to alanine (rxn_017) is well-supported (Miller-type). Convergent design is a strength but carries cumulative uncertainty from both acetolactate and transamination steps.', 'CO-based route through formaldehyde and UV-pyruvate synthesis. Multiple weakly supported steps accumulate uncertainty. The FTT formaldehyde synthesis (rxn_003) gives low yields, and the photochemical pyruvate synthesis (rxn_018) needs stronger support. Environmental oscillation reduces coherence.', 'Route from formate through formaldehyde to FTT isobutyraldehyde then Strecker. The connection between formaldehyde and isobutyraldehyde via FTT (rxn_010) is mechanistically unclear since rxn_010 uses CO+H\u2082 not formaldehyde. The pathway description appears inconsistent with the actual reaction substrates.', 'Surface-initiated route starting from photochemical pyruvate. Requires a formaldehyde source (additional upstream steps needed). Carries the acetolactate weakness. Reductive amination at the end requires return to hydrothermal conditions. The photochemical entry point is interesting but weakly supported.', 'Most comprehensive cross-environment pathway incorporating pyruvate regeneration cycle. Demonstrates the full network topology with Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow and pyruvate recycling. The catalytic cycle aspect (pyruvate consumed and regenerated) is a strength for sustained prebiotic production. Longest path with most accumulated uncertainty but showcases network connectivity.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Valine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"Multiple convergent prebiotic routes to valine through two principal branches: (A) Strecker synthesis from isobutyraldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083, and (B) reductive amination or transamination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate. Isobutyraldehyde is generated via cross-aldol condensation of propanal + formaldehyde on clay minerals (well-supported) and as a minor FTT product. \u03b1-Ketoisovalerate is accessed through both an acetolactate condensation route (speculative, acknowledged) and a cyanohydrin-oxidation route from isobutyraldehyde (better supported). HCN is explicitly synthesized from formaldehyde + NH\u2083 via formamide. Hub molecules (CO, formaldehyde, HCN, isobutyraldehyde, \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, pyruvate) create network density with clear Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical environmental flow.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon monoxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Carbon monoxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO/c1-2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHO2-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCONH2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Formamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"propanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Propanal\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O/c1-2-3-4/h3H,2H2,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-methylpropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H8O/c1-3(2)4-5/h3-4H,1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Pyruvate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8O4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-acetyl-2-hydroxypropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Acetolactate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H8O4/c1-3(6)5(2,9)4(7)8/h9H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"\u03b1-Ketoisovalerate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H8O3/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9N\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Valine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H10N2/c1-3(2)4(6)5-7/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H10O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"\u03b1-Hydroxyisovaleric acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H10O3/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4,6H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Alanine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"water\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H11NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Valine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H11NO2/c1-3(2)4(5)6(7)8/h3-4H,5H2,1-2H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"CO\u2082 reduction to CO via reverse water-gas shift\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\", \"elemental iron (Fe\u2070)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"450-550K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Deep-sea hydrothermal vent conditions, serpentinization-driven H\u2082 supply\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 adsorbs on magnetite surface and undergoes dissociative reduction by H\u2082 via the reverse water-gas shift reaction. Fe\u2070 provides additional reducing equivalents. CO is released as a gas phase product dissolved in hydrothermal fluid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The reverse water-gas shift reaction on iron oxide surfaces is thermodynamically favorable at high temperatures. Experimentally demonstrated in hydrothermal conditions by Seewald et al. (2006). CO is a critical C\u2081 building block for Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) synthesis. Magnetite is abundant in serpentinizing systems (McCollom & Seewald, 2007).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"CO\u2082 reduction to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>50 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline hydrothermal vent, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich fluid\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 is reduced to formate (HCOO\u207b) on the surface of greigite, which acts as an analog of biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters. The mineral provides both surface active sites and electron transfer capability from dissolved H\u2082.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Greigite-catalyzed CO\u2082 reduction to formate has been demonstrated experimentally by Roldan et al. (2015) under simulated hydrothermal vent conditions. Greigite is structurally analogous to the [Fe\u2084S\u2084] active site of carbon monoxide dehydrogenase/acetyl-CoA synthase (Russell & Martin, 2004). Yields of ~1-5% formate reported under mild alkaline vent conditions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate reduction to formaldehyde on mackinawite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mackinawite (FeS)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Strongly reducing conditions, pH ~9\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate is further reduced on mackinawite surfaces by H\u2082 to yield formaldehyde. The FeS surface provides a two-electron reduction pathway. Formaldehyde is partially stabilized by hydration (methylene glycol) in aqueous solution.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reduction of formate to formaldehyde on FeS surfaces has been proposed by Russell & Hall (1997) as part of the acetyl-CoA pathway analog. While formaldehyde yields are low due to further reduction, kinetic trapping by rapid export from the hot zone or reaction with other species (e.g., NH\u2083) can preserve the product (Herschy et al., 2014).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of formaldehyde from CO + H\u2082\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Fischer-Tropsch conditions, CO:H\u2082 ratio ~1:2\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO adsorbs on the magnetite surface and is hydrogenated stepwise to formaldehyde as the simplest C\u2081 oxygenated product. This is the first oxygenated intermediate in FTT synthesis before further chain growth to C\u2082+ products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formaldehyde is a known minor product of FTT synthesis on iron oxide catalysts at hydrothermal temperatures. McCollom et al. (1999) and McCollom & Seewald (2006) demonstrated formation of C\u2081-C\u2083 oxygenated compounds including formaldehyde under submarine hydrothermal conditions. This provides an alternative to the formate reduction route.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"FTT conditions, chain growth to C\u2082 oxygenate\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO undergoes chain growth via surface carbide/oxygenate mechanism on magnetite. C\u2081 surface intermediates couple and are hydrogenated to yield acetaldehyde as a C\u2082 oxygenated product. Anderson-Schulz-Flory distribution governs product selectivity.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Acetaldehyde is a well-documented product of FTT synthesis on magnetite and other iron-based catalysts. McCollom et al. (1999) detected C\u2082 aldehydes in FTT experiments at 175\u00b0C and 250 bar. Acetaldehyde is more thermodynamically accessible than longer-chain products under hydrothermal conditions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of propanal\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"FTT conditions, chain growth to C\u2083 oxygenate\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential CO insertion and hydrogenation on magnetite surface extends the carbon chain from C\u2082 to C\u2083, yielding propanal as a linear C\u2083 aldehyde. Selectivity follows Anderson-Schulz-Flory distribution with declining yield at higher chain lengths.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Propanal and other C\u2083 oxygenates are detected in FTT synthesis experiments, though at lower abundance than C\u2081-C\u2082 products. McCollom & Seewald (2006) observed C\u2083 alcohols and aldehydes in hydrothermal FTT experiments. Propanal is a critical precursor for generating branched C\u2084 architecture via aldol chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"CO\u2082 fixation to pyruvate on native iron/greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe\u2070)\", \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>50 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"native iron with greigite co-catalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Mildly alkaline pH, 1-3 day reaction time\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 is reduced in a multi-step process on Fe\u2070/Fe\u2083S\u2084 surfaces: first to formate, then to acetate, and finally to pyruvate through sequential C\u2081 additions with partial reduction. The mineral surfaces template a pathway analogous to the reductive acetyl-CoA/incomplete rTCA cycle.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Varma et al. (2018) demonstrated abiotic CO\u2082 fixation to pyruvate and other \u03b1-keto acids using Fe\u2070 and Ni\u2070 at 100\u00b0C under mildly acidic to neutral conditions. Pyruvate yields were low but reproducible. This represents a direct abiotic pathway to a central metabolic intermediate. Preiner et al. (2020) confirmed similar results with native metals simulating serpentinization-derived reducing conditions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Formaldehyde + ammonia condensation to formamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO\u2082 anatase (UV photocatalyst)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (200-300 nm), shallow evaporitic pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde reacts with ammonia in aqueous solution to form an aminomethanol intermediate (HOCH\u2082NH\u2082), which undergoes UV-assisted oxidation on TiO\u2082 to yield formamide (HCONH\u2082). TiO\u2082 generates hydroxyl radicals under UV irradiation that drive the selective oxidation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide synthesis from formaldehyde and ammonia is thermodynamically favorable. Saladino et al. (2012) extensively studied formamide as a prebiotic precursor in the presence of mineral catalysts. TiO\u2082 photocatalysis under UV can drive oxidation of aminomethanol to formamide (Botta et al., 2017). This reaction provides an explicit HCN precursor, addressing the need for an in-network HCN source.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide thermal dehydration to HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"340-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"Dry phase of wet-dry cycle, volcanic hot spring margin\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formamide undergoes thermal dehydration to hydrogen cyanide and water during the dry phase of wet-dry cycling. Montmorillonite clay acts as both a Br\u00f8nsted acid catalyst and a surface that concentrates formamide during evaporation, lowering the effective dehydration temperature.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide dehydration to HCN is a well-established reaction. Saladino et al. (2001, 2012) showed that formamide on mineral surfaces (clays, metal oxides) readily decomposes to HCN and other products at moderate temperatures. Montmorillonite catalyzes the reaction at temperatures as low as 60-80\u00b0C. This provides the in-network HCN production that was missing in previous network designs.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Cross-aldol condensation of propanal and formaldehyde to isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite with apatite (basic surface)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline evaporitic pool with wet-dry cycling, pH 8-10\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Propanal is enolized at its alpha-carbon by the basic montmorillonite/apatite surface. The enolate attacks formaldehyde in a cross-aldol reaction to yield 2-methyl-3-hydroxypropanal. During the dry phase, this intermediate undergoes dehydration to methacrolein (2-methylpropenal), which is then reduced to isobutyraldehyde by Fe\u00b2\u207a in the subsequent wet phase. The net reaction produces isobutyraldehyde and water.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cross-aldol condensation of aldehydes on clay minerals is well-established in prebiotic chemistry (Weber, 2001). Montmorillonite provides Br\u00f8nsted basic sites that catalyze enolization (Ferris et al., 1996). The dehydration-reduction sequence during wet-dry cycling is plausible with Fe\u00b2\u207a as a mild reductant (common in anoxic surface waters). This represents the primary prebiotically plausible route to branched C\u2084 aldehydes, providing the essential isobutyraldehyde needed for Strecker synthesis of valine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis: isobutyraldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 valine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (surface concentration)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Mildly alkaline pool, pH 8-9, ambient conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Isobutyraldehyde reacts with NH\u2083 to form an imine (Schiff base): (CH\u2083)\u2082CH-CH=NH. HCN then adds across the C=N bond via nucleophilic addition of cyanide to the iminium ion, yielding 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile (valine aminonitrile). Montmorillonite concentrates reactants and stabilizes the imine intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker synthesis is one of the most robust and well-established prebiotic amino acid synthesis routes. Miller (1957) demonstrated that Strecker intermediates (aminonitriles) form readily under simulated early Earth conditions. Isobutyraldehyde specifically yields valine aminonitrile as shown by Lerner et al. (1993). The reaction proceeds efficiently at ambient temperature in aqueous solution and is accelerated by clay mineral surfaces (Bujdak & Rode, 1999).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Valine aminonitrile hydrolysis to valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Mildly acidic or basic aqueous conditions, extended time (days-weeks)\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The nitrile group of valine aminonitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis: first to the amide (valine amide) by nucleophilic addition of water, then to the carboxylic acid (valine) with release of ammonia. The reaction is accelerated by mildly acidic conditions (pH 3-5) or by heating.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis to carboxylic acids is spontaneous in aqueous solution, with half-lives on the order of days to months at ambient temperature depending on pH (Schlesinger & Miller, 1983). This step is the final and most thermodynamically favorable step of the Strecker synthesis. Valine aminonitrile hydrolysis specifically has been confirmed in Miller-Urey experimental analyses (Parker et al., 2011).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate condensation to acetolactate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"330-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay with struvite (Mg\u00b2\u207a source)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Concentration during wet-dry cycling, Mg\u00b2\u207a and phosphate present\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate undergoes a crossed acyloin-type condensation with acetaldehyde. The methyl group of pyruvate is deprotonated on the basic clay surface, and the resulting carbanion attacks the carbonyl of acetaldehyde. The product is 2-acetyl-2-hydroxypropanoic acid (acetolactate). Mg\u00b2\u207a from struvite acts as a Lewis acid catalyst stabilizing the transition state.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"SPECULATIVE but supported by analogy: While biological acetolactate synthase requires thiamine pyrophosphate, the abiotic condensation of pyruvate with aldehydes has been observed under concentrated conditions with divalent metal ion catalysts (de Duve, 1991; Orgel, 2000). Montmorillonite concentration during wet-dry cycling provides the high effective concentrations needed. Mg\u00b2\u207a catalysis is proposed by analogy to metal-catalyzed decarboxylative condensations. This remains the least well-supported step in the acetolactate branch, but is included to provide pathway diversity.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetolactate rearrangement to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"340-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (acid-catalyzed)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Mildly acidic hot spring conditions, pH 4-6, extended heating\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetolactate undergoes acid-catalyzed dehydration to yield an enol intermediate, which tautomerizes and undergoes a pinacol-type 1,2-methyl shift on the clay surface. The rearrangement produces 3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid (\u03b1-ketoisovalerate) and water. Under acidic conditions, competitive decarboxylation to diacetyl is a side reaction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"SPECULATIVE: Biological conversion uses a [2Fe-2S] isomeroreductase, but non-enzymatic acid-catalyzed rearrangements of \u03b1-hydroxy ketones (pinacol-type) are well-known in organic chemistry. Acetolactate can non-enzymatically decarboxylate to acetoin or rearrange, and mineral surface catalysis could favor the rearrangement pathway over simple decarboxylation (Garg & Metzler, 1977). The low expected yield is compensated by the availability of alternative routes to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (rxn_016).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanohydrin formation and hydrolysis to \u03b1-hydroxyisovaleric acid\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (concentrator and mild base)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Aqueous pool, mildly alkaline pH 8-9\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN undergoes nucleophilic addition to the carbonyl of isobutyraldehyde to form the cyanohydrin (2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile). In aqueous solution, the nitrile group is subsequently hydrolyzed through the amide to the carboxylic acid, yielding 2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanoic acid (\u03b1-hydroxyisovaleric acid).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cyanohydrin formation from aldehydes and HCN is rapid and thermodynamically favorable under mildly basic conditions (Schlesinger & Miller, 1983). This is essentially the first step of Strecker synthesis but without ammonia, yielding a hydroxy acid rather than an amino acid. \u03b1-Hydroxy acids are common products of Miller-Urey experiments (Peltzer et al., 1984) and serve as direct precursors to \u03b1-keto acids via oxidation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"UV oxidation of \u03b1-hydroxyisovaleric acid to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO\u2082 anatase (UV photocatalyst)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (200-300 nm), shallow pool, no O\u2082 \u2014 Fe\u00b3\u207a or SO\u2084\u00b2\u207b as terminal oxidant\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"TiO\u2082 generates electron-hole pairs under UV irradiation. The hole oxidizes the alpha-hydroxyl group of \u03b1-hydroxyisovaleric acid to the corresponding ketone, yielding \u03b1-ketoisovalerate. Fe\u00b3\u207a (abundant on anoxic early Earth) serves as the terminal electron acceptor, being reduced to Fe\u00b2\u207a.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"UV-driven photocatalytic oxidation of alpha-hydroxy acids to alpha-keto acids on TiO\u2082 is well-established in photocatalysis literature (Bahnemann et al., 1991). Under anoxic early Earth conditions, Fe\u00b3\u207a or sulfate can serve as the terminal oxidant. This provides a second, better-supported route to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate that does not require the speculative acetolactate rearrangement, addressing a key weakness identified in the previous network.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate to valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"NH\u2083-rich alkaline vent fluid, reducing conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"\u03b1-Ketoisovalerate reacts with NH\u2083 to form an imine (Schiff base) intermediate. The C=N bond is then reduced by H\u2082 on the FeS/Fe\u2083S\u2084 mineral surface, yielding valine. The mineral surface provides both the reducing equivalents and a template for the stereoselective reduction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces has been demonstrated by Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003). The reaction of \u03b1-keto acids with ammonia under reducing hydrothermal conditions yields amino acids with moderate efficiency. Wang et al. (2005) showed that FeS minerals catalyze the reduction of Schiff bases. This provides a direct route from \u03b1-ketoisovalerate to valine under hydrothermal conditions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\", \"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite with pyrite as electron source\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"NH\u2083-rich alkaline vent, reducing conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate reacts with ammonia to form pyruvate imine. The imine is reduced by H\u2082 on greigite/pyrite surface to yield alanine. Pyrite oxidation provides additional reducing equivalents (FeS\u2082 \u2192 FeS + S\u2070 + 2e\u207b).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces is one of the best-supported prebiotic amino acid synthesis routes. Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2006) demonstrated this reaction experimentally. It is thermodynamically favorable under reducing hydrothermal conditions and represents the simplest reductive amination of an \u03b1-keto acid. Alanine is needed as an amino group donor for the transamination route to valine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_019\",\n      \"name\": \"Transamination: \u03b1-ketoisovalerate + alanine \u2192 valine + pyruvate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_017\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu\u00b2\u207a or Fe\u00b2\u207a ions (dissolved)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Metal-ion catalyzed, concentrated pool, pH 5-8\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Alanine forms a Schiff base with a divalent metal ion (Cu\u00b2\u207a or Fe\u00b2\u207a), activating the alpha-hydrogen for transfer. The amino group is transferred from alanine to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate via a pyridoxal-independent, metal-catalyzed mechanism involving ketimine/aldimine intermediates. Pyruvate is regenerated as a co-product, creating a catalytic cycle.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Metal-ion catalyzed transamination between amino acids and \u03b1-keto acids has been demonstrated without enzymatic catalysts by Snider & Wolfenden (2000). Cu\u00b2\u207a is particularly effective due to its ability to stabilize Schiff base intermediates (Metzler et al., 1954). The regeneration of pyruvate creates a catalytic cycle where pyruvate is consumed in alanine synthesis (rxn_018) and regenerated in transamination, enabling sustained valine production.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Primary Strecker pathway via aldol-derived isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"The most robust pathway: CO\u2082 \u2192 CO (hydrothermal) \u2192 propanal + formaldehyde (FTT) \u2192 isobutyraldehyde (aldol, surface) \u2192 valine aminonitrile (Strecker, surface) \u2192 valine (hydrolysis, biochemical). Formaldehyde also generates HCN via formamide for Strecker. Coherent Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate-to-formaldehyde Strecker pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Alternative formaldehyde source via formate: CO\u2082 \u2192 formate (on greigite) \u2192 formaldehyde (on mackinawite) \u2192 formamide \u2192 HCN (surface). Propanal from FTT. Aldol gives isobutyraldehyde. Strecker synthesis yields valine. Uses different mineral catalysts for C\u2081 generation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination via cyanohydrin-derived \u03b1-ketoisovalerate\",\n      \"description\": \"Isobutyraldehyde (from aldol, P1/P2) undergoes cyanohydrin formation with HCN \u2192 \u03b1-hydroxyisovaleric acid \u2192 UV oxidation on TiO\u2082 \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate \u2192 reductive amination on greigite \u2192 valine. Better-supported route to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate than acetolactate pathway.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetolactate route to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate then reductive amination\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (hydrothermal Fe\u2070/greigite, Varma et al. 2018). CO \u2192 acetaldehyde (FTT). Pyruvate + acetaldehyde \u2192 acetolactate \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (surface, speculative). Reductive amination on greigite \u2192 valine. Flow: Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Hydrothermal.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Transamination catalytic cycle pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Convergent pathway: pyruvate (hydrothermal) \u2192 alanine (reductive amination, hydrothermal) + \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (via cyanohydrin, surface) \u2192 valine + pyruvate (transamination, biochemical). Pyruvate is regenerated, creating a catalytic cycle. Demonstrates proto-metabolic network behavior.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Transamination via acetolactate-derived \u03b1-ketoisovalerate\",\n      \"description\": \"Combines acetolactate route to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate with transamination. Pyruvate \u2192 alanine (hydrothermal) + pyruvate + acetaldehyde \u2192 acetolactate \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (surface). Alanine + \u03b1-ketoisovalerate \u2192 valine + pyruvate (biochemical). Pyruvate recycled.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"All-surface Strecker with hydrothermal C\u2081/C\u2083 inputs\",\n      \"description\": \"Minimal hydrothermal footprint: only CO generation and FTT aldehyde synthesis in hydrothermal zone. All subsequent chemistry (HCN production, aldol, Strecker, hydrolysis) occurs in surface/biochemical environments. Demonstrates that vent chemistry primarily provides simple building blocks.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Dual-convergent pathway: both Strecker and reductive amination to valine\",\n      \"description\": \"Shows both terminal valine-forming reactions operating in parallel from shared isobutyraldehyde hub. Branch A: isobutyraldehyde \u2192 aminonitrile \u2192 valine (Strecker, surface/biochemical). Branch B: isobutyraldehyde \u2192 hydroxy acid \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate \u2192 valine (cyanohydrin-oxidation-reductive amination, surface/hydrothermal). Demonstrates redundancy.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate-only C\u2081 route with cyanohydrin branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Avoids CO/FTT: CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde (all hydrothermal FeS-catalyzed). Then formaldehyde \u2192 formamide \u2192 HCN (surface). Also CO\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate \u2192 alanine (hydrothermal). Uses propanal from separate FTT for aldol. Cyanohydrin route to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, then transamination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Complete network traversal \u2014 maximum environmental interconnection\",\n      \"description\": \"Showcases full network connectivity: CO\u2082 \u2192 CO (hydrothermal) \u2192 propanal + formaldehyde (hydrothermal FTT) \u2192 formamide \u2192 HCN (surface) + isobutyraldehyde (surface aldol) \u2192 \u03b1-hydroxyisovaleric acid (surface cyanohydrin) \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (surface UV) \u2192 valine (hydrothermal reductive amination). Simultaneously: CO\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate \u2192 alanine (hydrothermal) \u2192 transamination with \u03b1-ketoisovalerate \u2192 valine + pyruvate (biochemical). Complete Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical cycling with pyruvate regeneration.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_017\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_014\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde \u2014 central C\u2081 hub, produced by two independent hydrothermal routes\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN \u2014 nitrogen-carrying hub, produced via formamide from formaldehyde + NH\u2083\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"description\": \"Isobutyraldehyde \u2014 branched C\u2084 hub, key to generating valine's isopropyl sidechain\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"description\": \"\u03b1-Ketoisovalerate \u2014 branched C\u2085 hub, direct precursor to valine via amination or transamination, produced by two independent routes\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_017\", \"rxn_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate \u2014 central metabolic hub, produced by hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation and regenerated by transamination, connecting carbon fixation to amino acid synthesis\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\", \"rxn_018\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Valine", "overall_strategy": "Multiple convergent prebiotic routes to valine through two principal branches: (A) Strecker synthesis from isobutyraldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083, and (B) reductive amination or transamination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate. Isobutyraldehyde is generated via cross-aldol condensation of propanal + formaldehyde on clay minerals (well-supported) and as a minor FTT product. \u03b1-Ketoisovalerate is accessed through both an acetolactate condensation route (speculative, acknowledged) and a cyanohydrin-oxidation route from isobutyraldehyde (better supported). HCN is explicitly synthesized from formaldehyde + NH\u2083 via formamide. Hub molecules (CO, formaldehyde, HCN, isobutyraldehyde, \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, pyruvate) create network density with clear Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical environmental flow.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "Carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "Hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "ammonia", "common_name": "Ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "CO", "iupac_name": "carbon monoxide", "common_name": "Carbon monoxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO/c1-2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CHO2-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "Formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "formaldehyde", "common_name": "Formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "HCONH2", "iupac_name": "formamide", "common_name": "Formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "Hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "acetaldehyde", "common_name": "Acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C3H6O", "iupac_name": "propanal", "common_name": "Propanal", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O/c1-2-3-4/h3H,2H2,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C4H8O", "iupac_name": "2-methylpropanal", "common_name": "Isobutyraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8O/c1-3(2)4-5/h3-4H,1-2H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "Pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C5H8O4", "iupac_name": "2-acetyl-2-hydroxypropanoic acid", "common_name": "Acetolactate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H8O4/c1-3(6)5(2,9)4(7)8/h9H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C5H8O3", "iupac_name": "3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid", "common_name": "\u03b1-Ketoisovalerate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H8O3/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C5H9N", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile", "common_name": "Valine aminonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H10N2/c1-3(2)4(6)5-7/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C5H10O3", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanoic acid", "common_name": "\u03b1-Hydroxyisovaleric acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H10O3/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4,6H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "Alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "water", "common_name": "Water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C5H11NO2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid", "common_name": "Valine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H11NO2/c1-3(2)4(5)6(7)8/h3-4H,5H2,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "CO\u2082 reduction to CO via reverse water-gas shift", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_004", "mol_018"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "elemental iron (Fe\u2070)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "450-550K", "pressure": "high (>100 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Deep-sea hydrothermal vent conditions, serpentinization-driven H\u2082 supply"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 adsorbs on magnetite surface and undergoes dissociative reduction by H\u2082 via the reverse water-gas shift reaction. Fe\u2070 provides additional reducing equivalents. CO is released as a gas phase product dissolved in hydrothermal fluid.", "reasoning": "The reverse water-gas shift reaction on iron oxide surfaces is thermodynamically favorable at high temperatures. Experimentally demonstrated in hydrothermal conditions by Seewald et al. (2006). CO is a critical C\u2081 building block for Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) synthesis. Magnetite is abundant in serpentinizing systems (McCollom & Seewald, 2007)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "CO\u2082 reduction to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (>50 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline hydrothermal vent, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich fluid"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 is reduced to formate (HCOO\u207b) on the surface of greigite, which acts as an analog of biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters. The mineral provides both surface active sites and electron transfer capability from dissolved H\u2082.", "reasoning": "Greigite-catalyzed CO\u2082 reduction to formate has been demonstrated experimentally by Roldan et al. (2015) under simulated hydrothermal vent conditions. Greigite is structurally analogous to the [Fe\u2084S\u2084] active site of carbon monoxide dehydrogenase/acetyl-CoA synthase (Russell & Martin, 2004). Yields of ~1-5% formate reported under mild alkaline vent conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Formate reduction to formaldehyde on mackinawite", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "mackinawite (FeS)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Strongly reducing conditions, pH ~9"}, "mechanism": "Formate is further reduced on mackinawite surfaces by H\u2082 to yield formaldehyde. The FeS surface provides a two-electron reduction pathway. Formaldehyde is partially stabilized by hydration (methylene glycol) in aqueous solution.", "reasoning": "Reduction of formate to formaldehyde on FeS surfaces has been proposed by Russell & Hall (1997) as part of the acetyl-CoA pathway analog. While formaldehyde yields are low due to further reduction, kinetic trapping by rapid export from the hot zone or reaction with other species (e.g., NH\u2083) can preserve the product (Herschy et al., 2014)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of formaldehyde from CO + H\u2082", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (>100 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Fischer-Tropsch conditions, CO:H\u2082 ratio ~1:2"}, "mechanism": "CO adsorbs on the magnetite surface and is hydrogenated stepwise to formaldehyde as the simplest C\u2081 oxygenated product. This is the first oxygenated intermediate in FTT synthesis before further chain growth to C\u2082+ products.", "reasoning": "Formaldehyde is a known minor product of FTT synthesis on iron oxide catalysts at hydrothermal temperatures. McCollom et al. (1999) and McCollom & Seewald (2006) demonstrated formation of C\u2081-C\u2083 oxygenated compounds including formaldehyde under submarine hydrothermal conditions. This provides an alternative to the formate reduction route."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (>100 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "FTT conditions, chain growth to C\u2082 oxygenate"}, "mechanism": "CO undergoes chain growth via surface carbide/oxygenate mechanism on magnetite. C\u2081 surface intermediates couple and are hydrogenated to yield acetaldehyde as a C\u2082 oxygenated product. Anderson-Schulz-Flory distribution governs product selectivity.", "reasoning": "Acetaldehyde is a well-documented product of FTT synthesis on magnetite and other iron-based catalysts. McCollom et al. (1999) detected C\u2082 aldehydes in FTT experiments at 175\u00b0C and 250 bar. Acetaldehyde is more thermodynamically accessible than longer-chain products under hydrothermal conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of propanal", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (>100 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "FTT conditions, chain growth to C\u2083 oxygenate"}, "mechanism": "Sequential CO insertion and hydrogenation on magnetite surface extends the carbon chain from C\u2082 to C\u2083, yielding propanal as a linear C\u2083 aldehyde. Selectivity follows Anderson-Schulz-Flory distribution with declining yield at higher chain lengths.", "reasoning": "Propanal and other C\u2083 oxygenates are detected in FTT synthesis experiments, though at lower abundance than C\u2081-C\u2082 products. McCollom & Seewald (2006) observed C\u2083 alcohols and aldehydes in hydrothermal FTT experiments. Propanal is a critical precursor for generating branched C\u2084 architecture via aldol chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "CO\u2082 fixation to pyruvate on native iron/greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe\u2070)", "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (>50 bar)", "catalyst": "native iron with greigite co-catalyst", "aqueous": true, "other": "Mildly alkaline pH, 1-3 day reaction time"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 is reduced in a multi-step process on Fe\u2070/Fe\u2083S\u2084 surfaces: first to formate, then to acetate, and finally to pyruvate through sequential C\u2081 additions with partial reduction. The mineral surfaces template a pathway analogous to the reductive acetyl-CoA/incomplete rTCA cycle.", "reasoning": "Varma et al. (2018) demonstrated abiotic CO\u2082 fixation to pyruvate and other \u03b1-keto acids using Fe\u2070 and Ni\u2070 at 100\u00b0C under mildly acidic to neutral conditions. Pyruvate yields were low but reproducible. This represents a direct abiotic pathway to a central metabolic intermediate. Preiner et al. (2020) confirmed similar results with native metals simulating serpentinization-derived reducing conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Formaldehyde + ammonia condensation to formamide", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO\u2082 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO\u2082 anatase (UV photocatalyst)", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation (200-300 nm), shallow evaporitic pool"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde reacts with ammonia in aqueous solution to form an aminomethanol intermediate (HOCH\u2082NH\u2082), which undergoes UV-assisted oxidation on TiO\u2082 to yield formamide (HCONH\u2082). TiO\u2082 generates hydroxyl radicals under UV irradiation that drive the selective oxidation.", "reasoning": "Formamide synthesis from formaldehyde and ammonia is thermodynamically favorable. Saladino et al. (2012) extensively studied formamide as a prebiotic precursor in the presence of mineral catalysts. TiO\u2082 photocatalysis under UV can drive oxidation of aminomethanol to formamide (Botta et al., 2017). This reaction provides an explicit HCN precursor, addressing the need for an in-network HCN source."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Formamide thermal dehydration to HCN", "inputs": ["mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008", "mol_018"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "340-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay", "aqueous": false, "other": "Dry phase of wet-dry cycle, volcanic hot spring margin"}, "mechanism": "Formamide undergoes thermal dehydration to hydrogen cyanide and water during the dry phase of wet-dry cycling. Montmorillonite clay acts as both a Br\u00f8nsted acid catalyst and a surface that concentrates formamide during evaporation, lowering the effective dehydration temperature.", "reasoning": "Formamide dehydration to HCN is a well-established reaction. Saladino et al. (2001, 2012) showed that formamide on mineral surfaces (clays, metal oxides) readily decomposes to HCN and other products at moderate temperatures. Montmorillonite catalyzes the reaction at temperatures as low as 60-80\u00b0C. This provides the in-network HCN production that was missing in previous network designs."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Cross-aldol condensation of propanal and formaldehyde to isobutyraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_011", "mol_018"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite with apatite (basic surface)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline evaporitic pool with wet-dry cycling, pH 8-10"}, "mechanism": "Propanal is enolized at its alpha-carbon by the basic montmorillonite/apatite surface. The enolate attacks formaldehyde in a cross-aldol reaction to yield 2-methyl-3-hydroxypropanal. During the dry phase, this intermediate undergoes dehydration to methacrolein (2-methylpropenal), which is then reduced to isobutyraldehyde by Fe\u00b2\u207a in the subsequent wet phase. The net reaction produces isobutyraldehyde and water.", "reasoning": "Cross-aldol condensation of aldehydes on clay minerals is well-established in prebiotic chemistry (Weber, 2001). Montmorillonite provides Br\u00f8nsted basic sites that catalyze enolization (Ferris et al., 1996). The dehydration-reduction sequence during wet-dry cycling is plausible with Fe\u00b2\u207a as a mild reductant (common in anoxic surface waters). This represents the primary prebiotically plausible route to branched C\u2084 aldehydes, providing the essential isobutyraldehyde needed for Strecker synthesis of valine."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Strecker synthesis: isobutyraldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 valine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_008", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (surface concentration)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Mildly alkaline pool, pH 8-9, ambient conditions"}, "mechanism": "Isobutyraldehyde reacts with NH\u2083 to form an imine (Schiff base): (CH\u2083)\u2082CH-CH=NH. HCN then adds across the C=N bond via nucleophilic addition of cyanide to the iminium ion, yielding 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile (valine aminonitrile). Montmorillonite concentrates reactants and stabilizes the imine intermediate.", "reasoning": "The Strecker synthesis is one of the most robust and well-established prebiotic amino acid synthesis routes. Miller (1957) demonstrated that Strecker intermediates (aminonitriles) form readily under simulated early Earth conditions. Isobutyraldehyde specifically yields valine aminonitrile as shown by Lerner et al. (1993). The reaction proceeds efficiently at ambient temperature in aqueous solution and is accelerated by clay mineral surfaces (Bujdak & Rode, 1999)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Valine aminonitrile hydrolysis to valine", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_018"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "Mildly acidic or basic aqueous conditions, extended time (days-weeks)"}, "mechanism": "The nitrile group of valine aminonitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis: first to the amide (valine amide) by nucleophilic addition of water, then to the carboxylic acid (valine) with release of ammonia. The reaction is accelerated by mildly acidic conditions (pH 3-5) or by heating.", "reasoning": "Nitrile hydrolysis to carboxylic acids is spontaneous in aqueous solution, with half-lives on the order of days to months at ambient temperature depending on pH (Schlesinger & Miller, 1983). This step is the final and most thermodynamically favorable step of the Strecker synthesis. Valine aminonitrile hydrolysis specifically has been confirmed in Miller-Urey experimental analyses (Parker et al., 2011)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Pyruvate condensation to acetolactate", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "330-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay with struvite (Mg\u00b2\u207a source)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Concentration during wet-dry cycling, Mg\u00b2\u207a and phosphate present"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate undergoes a crossed acyloin-type condensation with acetaldehyde. The methyl group of pyruvate is deprotonated on the basic clay surface, and the resulting carbanion attacks the carbonyl of acetaldehyde. The product is 2-acetyl-2-hydroxypropanoic acid (acetolactate). Mg\u00b2\u207a from struvite acts as a Lewis acid catalyst stabilizing the transition state.", "reasoning": "SPECULATIVE but supported by analogy: While biological acetolactate synthase requires thiamine pyrophosphate, the abiotic condensation of pyruvate with aldehydes has been observed under concentrated conditions with divalent metal ion catalysts (de Duve, 1991; Orgel, 2000). Montmorillonite concentration during wet-dry cycling provides the high effective concentrations needed. Mg\u00b2\u207a catalysis is proposed by analogy to metal-catalyzed decarboxylative condensations. This remains the least well-supported step in the acetolactate branch, but is included to provide pathway diversity."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Acetolactate rearrangement to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_014", "mol_018"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "340-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (acid-catalyzed)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Mildly acidic hot spring conditions, pH 4-6, extended heating"}, "mechanism": "Acetolactate undergoes acid-catalyzed dehydration to yield an enol intermediate, which tautomerizes and undergoes a pinacol-type 1,2-methyl shift on the clay surface. The rearrangement produces 3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid (\u03b1-ketoisovalerate) and water. Under acidic conditions, competitive decarboxylation to diacetyl is a side reaction.", "reasoning": "SPECULATIVE: Biological conversion uses a [2Fe-2S] isomeroreductase, but non-enzymatic acid-catalyzed rearrangements of \u03b1-hydroxy ketones (pinacol-type) are well-known in organic chemistry. Acetolactate can non-enzymatically decarboxylate to acetoin or rearrange, and mineral surface catalysis could favor the rearrangement pathway over simple decarboxylation (Garg & Metzler, 1977). The low expected yield is compensated by the availability of alternative routes to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (rxn_016)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Cyanohydrin formation and hydrolysis to \u03b1-hydroxyisovaleric acid", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_008", "mol_018"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (concentrator and mild base)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Aqueous pool, mildly alkaline pH 8-9"}, "mechanism": "HCN undergoes nucleophilic addition to the carbonyl of isobutyraldehyde to form the cyanohydrin (2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile). In aqueous solution, the nitrile group is subsequently hydrolyzed through the amide to the carboxylic acid, yielding 2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanoic acid (\u03b1-hydroxyisovaleric acid).", "reasoning": "Cyanohydrin formation from aldehydes and HCN is rapid and thermodynamically favorable under mildly basic conditions (Schlesinger & Miller, 1983). This is essentially the first step of Strecker synthesis but without ammonia, yielding a hydroxy acid rather than an amino acid. \u03b1-Hydroxy acids are common products of Miller-Urey experiments (Peltzer et al., 1984) and serve as direct precursors to \u03b1-keto acids via oxidation."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "UV oxidation of \u03b1-hydroxyisovaleric acid to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate", "inputs": ["mol_016"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO\u2082 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO\u2082 anatase (UV photocatalyst)", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation (200-300 nm), shallow pool, no O\u2082 \u2014 Fe\u00b3\u207a or SO\u2084\u00b2\u207b as terminal oxidant"}, "mechanism": "TiO\u2082 generates electron-hole pairs under UV irradiation. The hole oxidizes the alpha-hydroxyl group of \u03b1-hydroxyisovaleric acid to the corresponding ketone, yielding \u03b1-ketoisovalerate. Fe\u00b3\u207a (abundant on anoxic early Earth) serves as the terminal electron acceptor, being reduced to Fe\u00b2\u207a.", "reasoning": "UV-driven photocatalytic oxidation of alpha-hydroxy acids to alpha-keto acids on TiO\u2082 is well-established in photocatalysis literature (Bahnemann et al., 1991). Under anoxic early Earth conditions, Fe\u00b3\u207a or sulfate can serve as the terminal oxidant. This provides a second, better-supported route to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate that does not require the speculative acetolactate rearrangement, addressing a key weakness identified in the previous network."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate to valine", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "NH\u2083-rich alkaline vent fluid, reducing conditions"}, "mechanism": "\u03b1-Ketoisovalerate reacts with NH\u2083 to form an imine (Schiff base) intermediate. The C=N bond is then reduced by H\u2082 on the FeS/Fe\u2083S\u2084 mineral surface, yielding valine. The mineral surface provides both the reducing equivalents and a template for the stereoselective reduction.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces has been demonstrated by Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003). The reaction of \u03b1-keto acids with ammonia under reducing hydrothermal conditions yields amino acids with moderate efficiency. Wang et al. (2005) showed that FeS minerals catalyze the reduction of Schiff bases. This provides a direct route from \u03b1-ketoisovalerate to valine under hydrothermal conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "pyrite (FeS\u2082)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite with pyrite as electron source", "aqueous": true, "other": "NH\u2083-rich alkaline vent, reducing conditions"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate reacts with ammonia to form pyruvate imine. The imine is reduced by H\u2082 on greigite/pyrite surface to yield alanine. Pyrite oxidation provides additional reducing equivalents (FeS\u2082 \u2192 FeS + S\u2070 + 2e\u207b).", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces is one of the best-supported prebiotic amino acid synthesis routes. Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2006) demonstrated this reaction experimentally. It is thermodynamically favorable under reducing hydrothermal conditions and represents the simplest reductive amination of an \u03b1-keto acid. Alanine is needed as an amino group donor for the transamination route to valine."}, {"id": "rxn_019", "name": "Transamination: \u03b1-ketoisovalerate + alanine \u2192 valine + pyruvate", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_017"], "outputs": ["mol_019", "mol_012"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu\u00b2\u207a or Fe\u00b2\u207a ions (dissolved)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Metal-ion catalyzed, concentrated pool, pH 5-8"}, "mechanism": "Alanine forms a Schiff base with a divalent metal ion (Cu\u00b2\u207a or Fe\u00b2\u207a), activating the alpha-hydrogen for transfer. The amino group is transferred from alanine to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate via a pyridoxal-independent, metal-catalyzed mechanism involving ketimine/aldimine intermediates. Pyruvate is regenerated as a co-product, creating a catalytic cycle.", "reasoning": "Metal-ion catalyzed transamination between amino acids and \u03b1-keto acids has been demonstrated without enzymatic catalysts by Snider & Wolfenden (2000). Cu\u00b2\u207a is particularly effective due to its ability to stabilize Schiff base intermediates (Metzler et al., 1954). The regeneration of pyruvate creates a catalytic cycle where pyruvate is consumed in alanine synthesis (rxn_018) and regenerated in transamination, enabling sustained valine production."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Primary Strecker pathway via aldol-derived isobutyraldehyde", "description": "The most robust pathway: CO\u2082 \u2192 CO (hydrothermal) \u2192 propanal + formaldehyde (FTT) \u2192 isobutyraldehyde (aldol, surface) \u2192 valine aminonitrile (Strecker, surface) \u2192 valine (hydrolysis, biochemical). Formaldehyde also generates HCN via formamide for Strecker. Coherent Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_006", "rxn_004", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_010", "mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_011", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Formate-to-formaldehyde Strecker pathway", "description": "Alternative formaldehyde source via formate: CO\u2082 \u2192 formate (on greigite) \u2192 formaldehyde (on mackinawite) \u2192 formamide \u2192 HCN (surface). Propanal from FTT. Aldol gives isobutyraldehyde. Strecker synthesis yields valine. Uses different mineral catalysts for C\u2081 generation.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_001", "rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_010", "mol_008", "mol_011", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Reductive amination via cyanohydrin-derived \u03b1-ketoisovalerate", "description": "Isobutyraldehyde (from aldol, P1/P2) undergoes cyanohydrin formation with HCN \u2192 \u03b1-hydroxyisovaleric acid \u2192 UV oxidation on TiO\u2082 \u2192 \u