{"timestamp": "2026-03-17T05:59:04.065014", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Valine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.8\n- Feedback: This is a well-designed and comprehensive prebiotic synthesis network for valine with strong topological properties. The network features 17 molecules, 18 reactions, 10 pathways, and 5 convergence points, demonstrating excellent redundancy and interconnection. Key strengths: (1) Hub molecules are well-chosen with pyruvate, \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, CO, and NH\u2083 serving as proper high-connectivity nodes; (2) Multiple routes to the target provide robustness; (3) Environmental flow is generally well-managed with clear Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical progression; (4) The Strecker synthesis portions are well-established chemistry; (5) Mineral catalysts are specified for hydrothermal reactions. Key weaknesses: (1) The acetolactate pathway (rxn_007 \u2192 rxn_008) is the critical bottleneck\u2014abiotic pyruvate condensation to acetolactate without thiamine and the subsequent complex rearrangement to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate are the least supported steps; (2) HCN (mol_004) is used as a reactant in Strecker reactions but has no production reaction in the network\u2014it should either be designated as a starting material or given a synthesis reaction (e.g., from NH\u2083 + CH\u2082O or spark discharge); (3) Fischer-Tropsch selectivity for branched isobutyraldehyde (rxn_010) is not well-justified. The network achieves a passing confidence of 0.80 primarily because the diversity of routes ensures that at least P4 (through Strecker synthesis) provides a chemically coherent and environmentally progressive pathway to valine, even if some individual steps carry uncertainty.\n- Issues: ['Direct route through the biosynthetic-like acetolactate pathway. The pyruvate condensation to acetolactate (rxn_007) without thiamine is prebiotically uncertain, and the acetolactate-to-\u03b1-ketoisovalerate step (rxn_008) compresses a complex multi-step biological transformation (reduction, isomerization, dehydration) into a single surface reaction. Environmental flow is slightly awkward: Hydrothermal \u2192 Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Hydrothermal.', 'Longest route to valine through formate and formaldehyde. The UV-driven formaldehyde-to-pyruvate step (rxn_018) on TiO\u2082 is interesting but not strongly supported experimentally. Carries the same acetolactate pathway weakness as P1. Environmental flow oscillates: Hydrothermal \u2192 Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Hydrothermal.', 'Elegant short pathway through Fischer-Tropsch isobutyraldehyde and Strecker synthesis. The main weakness is the selectivity of FTT for branched C\u2084 aldehyde (rxn_010); FTT typically produces linear alkanes/alcohols and the branched aldehyde yield would be very low. The Strecker portion is well-established. Good environmental flow: Hydrothermal \u2192 Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Surface.', 'Convergent pathway requiring both \u03b1-ketoisovalerate and alanine. Transamination (rxn_015) is plausible with metal ion catalysis (Cu\u00b2\u207a, Fe\u00b2\u207a) but less efficient without pyridoxal phosphate. The convergent topology is a strength, and pyruvate regeneration creates a catalytic cycle. Same acetolactate bottleneck persists. Environmental flow: Hydrothermal \u2192 Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface + Hydrothermal \u2192 Biochemical.', 'Cross-environment pathway using surface Strecker alanine with hydrothermal \u03b1-ketoisovalerate for transamination. The acetaldehyde Strecker route to alanine (rxn_017) is well-supported (Miller-type). Convergent design is a strength but carries cumulative uncertainty from both acetolactate and transamination steps.', 'CO-based route through formaldehyde and UV-pyruvate synthesis. Multiple weakly supported steps accumulate uncertainty. The FTT formaldehyde synthesis (rxn_003) gives low yields, and the photochemical pyruvate synthesis (rxn_018) needs stronger support. Environmental oscillation reduces coherence.', 'Route from formate through formaldehyde to FTT isobutyraldehyde then Strecker. The connection between formaldehyde and isobutyraldehyde via FTT (rxn_010) is mechanistically unclear since rxn_010 uses CO+H\u2082 not formaldehyde. The pathway description appears inconsistent with the actual reaction substrates.', 'Surface-initiated route starting from photochemical pyruvate. Requires a formaldehyde source (additional upstream steps needed). Carries the acetolactate weakness. Reductive amination at the end requires return to hydrothermal conditions. The photochemical entry point is interesting but weakly supported.', 'Most comprehensive cross-environment pathway incorporating pyruvate regeneration cycle. Demonstrates the full network topology with Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow and pyruvate recycling. The catalytic cycle aspect (pyruvate consumed and regenerated) is a strength for sustained prebiotic production. Longest path with most accumulated uncertainty but showcases network connectivity.']\n\nAttempt 2:\n- Confidence: 0.84\n- Feedback: This is a well-constructed prebiotic synthesis network for valine with excellent topological structure. The 19 molecule / 19 reaction architecture provides genuine redundancy through three independent terminal routes (Strecker, reductive amination, transamination). The five hub molecules (CO, formaldehyde, HCN, isobutyraldehyde, \u03b1-ketoisovalerate) create meaningful connectivity, and the environmental flow from hydrothermal C1 generation through surface Strecker/aldol chemistry to biochemical hydrolysis is well-articulated. The primary Strecker pathway via aldol-derived isobutyraldehyde is the strongest and best-supported route. The acetolactate branch (rxn_013, rxn_014) is the weakest element \u2014 both steps lack clear prebiotic experimental precedent. The strategy of acknowledging this speculation is commendable. The cyanohydrin-oxidation route to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (rxn_015-016) provides a more plausible alternative to the acetolactate pathway. Key strengths: (1) multiple convergent routes to valine, (2) explicit HCN synthesis pathway, (3) well-defined hub molecule network, (4) clear environmental staging. Key weaknesses: (1) FTT propanal yield likely very low, (2) acetolactate chemistry is speculative, (3) UV oxidation selectivity uncertain, (4) no explicit literature citations in reaction reasoning. Overall this network meets the threshold for approval.\n- Issues: ['The acetolactate route is the most speculative pathway. While pyruvate synthesis on native iron (rxn_007) is well-supported by Varma et al., the condensation of pyruvate with acetaldehyde to form acetolactate (rxn_013) is enzymatic in biology (acetolactate synthase, TPP-dependent). Non-enzymatic acetolactate formation is poorly established. The subsequent rearrangement/decarboxylation to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (rxn_014) also lacks prebiotic precedent without enzymes.', 'The transamination cycle pathway is conceptually elegant \u2014 using alanine as amino donor for \u03b1-ketoisovalerate with pyruvate recycling. Transamination (rxn_019) is plausible with metal ion catalysts (Cu\u00b2\u207a, Fe\u00b2\u207a) or pyridoxal-like species but represents a more complex biochemical-like mechanism. The overall pathway coherence is good but the long chain of steps reduces confidence.', 'Combines the two weakest mechanistic steps in the network: acetolactate formation/rearrangement and transamination. While each individual step has some plausibility, stacking two speculative transformations significantly reduces overall confidence. This pathway represents a biochemical-like route that would be more relevant in a proto-enzymatic context.', 'Long pathway with formate as sole C1 entry point. The formate \u2192 formaldehyde step remains questionable. The length (12 steps) introduces cumulative yield concerns. However, it demonstrates network richness and avoids reliance on FTT for anything other than simple C1 species.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Valine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This network generates valine through three independent terminal routes\u2014Strecker synthesis, reductive amination, and transamination\u2014all converging from prebiotically plausible C1-C4 building blocks. The strategy avoids the speculative acetolactate pathway entirely, instead using Varma et al.-type reductive carboxylation of isobutyraldehyde to generate \u03b1-ketoisovalerate. Hydrothermal environments produce C1 species (CO, formate, formaldehyde) and small aldehydes (acetaldehyde, propanal) via Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry on mineral catalysts. Surface environments drive aldol condensation, HCN synthesis, and Strecker chemistry. Biochemical environments enable transamination and final macromolecular-level assembly. Hub molecules (formaldehyde, HCN, isobutyraldehyde, \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, pyruvate) create genuine convergence points where multiple independent routes intersect, providing redundancy and robustness.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"dihydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen gas\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"water\",\n      \"common_name\": \"water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon monoxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon monoxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO/c1-2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHOO-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"propanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"propanal\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O/c1-2-3-4/h3H,2H2,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-methylpropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H8O/c1-3(2)4-5/h3-4H,1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H10N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alpha-aminoisovaleronitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H10N2/c1-3(2)4(6)5-7/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H3O3-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H7O3-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-methyl-2-oxobutanoate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alpha-ketoisovalerate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H8O3/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alanine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-methylprop-2-enal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"methacrolein\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H6O/c1-3(2)4-5/h4H,1H2,2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H11NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"valine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H11NO2/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H5NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminoacetic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H7NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"isobutyraldehyde cyanohydrin\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO/c1-3(2)4(6)5-7/h3-4,6H,1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"CO\u2082 reduction to CO via reverse water-gas shift on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-400 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"serpentinization-derived H\u2082\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reverse water-gas shift reaction: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 CO + H\u2082O catalyzed on magnetite surfaces at hydrothermal temperatures. CO\u2082 adsorbs on Fe\u00b3\u207a sites and is reduced by H\u2082 dissociated on the mineral surface.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Magnetite-catalyzed reverse water-gas shift is well-established in hydrothermal experiments. Seewald et al. (2006) demonstrated CO\u2082-CO interconversion under hydrothermal conditions. Magnetite is a known catalyst for this reaction at 400-500K (McCollom & Seewald, 2007). CO is a critical C1 feedstock for subsequent Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"CO\u2082 reduction to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-300 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 is adsorbed onto the greigite surface, which acts as an analog of biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters. Hydride transfer from surface-bound H\u2082 reduces CO\u2082 to formate (HCOO\u207b) via a two-electron reduction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Roldan et al. (2015) demonstrated that greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084) reduces CO\u2082 to formate under mild hydrothermal conditions, drawing the analogy between greigite and the [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters in carbon-fixing enzymes like CO dehydrogenase/acetyl-CoA synthase. Herschy et al. (2014) confirmed formate production in simulated alkaline vent conditions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type formaldehyde synthesis from CO\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-400 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"FTT synthesis regime, CO:H\u2082 \u2248 1:2\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO hydrogenation on magnetite surface via Fischer-Tropsch-type mechanism. CO adsorbs on iron surface, H\u2082 dissociates, and stepwise hydrogenation yields formaldehyde (the C1 oxygenate product). Partial hydrogenation is favored at lower residence times.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"McCollom et al. (1999) and McCollom & Seewald (2006) demonstrated FTT synthesis of small oxygenates including formaldehyde on magnetite surfaces under hydrothermal conditions. Formaldehyde is the simplest aldehyde product and serves as a C1 building block for subsequent aldol chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate reduction to formaldehyde on native iron\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe\u2070)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-300 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"elemental iron (Fe\u2070)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mildly alkaline, reducing conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Two-electron reduction of formate on native iron surface. Fe\u2070 acts as electron donor, reducing the carboxylate group of formate to the aldehyde oxidation state, yielding formaldehyde. Fe\u2070 is oxidized to Fe\u00b2\u207a.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Varma et al. (2018) showed that native iron (Fe\u2070) in aqueous conditions acts as a potent reductant capable of multi-electron reductions of C1 species. The reduction of formate to formaldehyde is thermodynamically favorable with Fe\u2070 as reductant under mildly alkaline hydrothermal conditions. This provides an alternative formaldehyde source independent of CO-based FTT.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of C2-C3 aldehydes\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"420-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (200-500 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"FTT regime with chain growth, Anderson-Schulz-Flory distribution\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type chain growth on magnetite surface. CO and H\u2082 undergo repeated C1 insertion and hydrogenation steps. Chain termination via oxygenate pathway yields linear aldehydes: acetaldehyde (C2) and propanal (C3) as products following Anderson-Schulz-Flory distribution.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"McCollom et al. (1999) demonstrated FTT synthesis of linear C1-C5 oxygenates (alcohols, aldehydes) on magnetite catalysts under hydrothermal conditions. Acetaldehyde and propanal are well-established FTT products with reasonable yields. Rushdi & Simoneit (2001) confirmed the formation of C2-C4 oxygenates in FTT experiments.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Photochemical HCN synthesis from NH\u2083 and formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (\u03bb < 300 nm), no ozone layer, gas-phase or thin film\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV photolysis of formaldehyde generates radical intermediates. TiO\u2082 photocatalysis generates reactive oxygen species and surface radicals. Ammonia reacts with formaldehyde-derived radicals (\u00b7CHO, \u00b7CH\u2082OH) on TiO\u2082 surface to form aminomethanol, which dehydrates to formaldimine (CH\u2082=NH), then further dehydrogenation under UV yields HCN.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ferris & Hagan (1984) demonstrated HCN production from NH\u2083 and CH\u2082O under UV irradiation. TiO\u2082 photocatalysis enhances this reaction (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012). HCN is also produced volcanically, but this synthetic route from prebiotically available HCHO and NH\u2083 ensures the network is self-contained. HCN is essential for Strecker synthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Cross-aldol condensation of propanal with formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mildly alkaline pH 8-10, wet-dry cycling promotes concentration\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Base-catalyzed cross-aldol condensation. The alpha-proton of propanal is abstracted by basic sites on montmorillonite. The resulting enolate attacks the carbonyl of formaldehyde to give 2-(hydroxymethyl)propanal. Subsequent dehydration (promoted by dry phase of wet-dry cycle) yields methacrolein (2-methylprop-2-enal).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aldol condensations between small aldehydes are well-established in prebiotic chemistry. Weber (1992, 2001) demonstrated sugar synthesis via aldol reactions under prebiotic conditions. Montmorillonite catalyzes aldol reactions through its Br\u00f8nsted acid/base sites and concentrates organics via adsorption (Ferris, 2005). Cross-aldol of propanal with formaldehyde is thermodynamically favored because formaldehyde has no alpha-H and acts exclusively as the electrophile.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduction of methacrolein to isobutyraldehyde on pyrite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite/mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"FeS as electron donor, mildly acidic to neutral pH\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Selective hydrogenation of the C=C double bond in methacrolein while preserving the aldehyde group. FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces donate electrons for the reduction. H\u2082 dissociates on pyrite surface providing H atoms for 1,4-conjugate addition across the \u03b1,\u03b2-unsaturated aldehyde system, yielding the saturated isobutyraldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyrite and mackinawite surfaces are known to catalyze reductions of organic molecules. W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1988, 1992) proposed FeS/FeS\u2082 as primordial reducing agents. Cody et al. (2004) demonstrated that metal sulfide surfaces can selectively reduce unsaturated organic compounds. The selective 1,4-reduction of an \u03b1,\u03b2-unsaturated aldehyde to a saturated aldehyde is thermodynamically favorable and well-established in heterogeneous catalysis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct FTT synthesis of isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\", \"elemental iron (Fe\u2070)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"450-550K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (200-500 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite with Fe\u2070 co-catalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"FTT conditions favoring branching, higher temperature regime\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type chain growth with branch formation. At higher temperatures, secondary carbon radical intermediates on the catalyst surface undergo \u03b2-hydride elimination and re-insertion, creating branched products. Chain termination by CO insertion and hydrogenation at the branch point yields 2-methylpropanal (isobutyraldehyde) as a minor branched C4 product.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"While FTT primarily yields linear products following Anderson-Schulz-Flory distribution, branched products including isobutyraldehyde have been detected in FTT experiments at elevated temperatures (Rushdi & Simoneit, 2001). The branching fraction increases with temperature. Yields are low (typically <5% of C4 fraction is branched), but this provides an alternative hydrothermal route to isobutyraldehyde independent of the aldol pathway. McCollom & Seewald (2007) note that FTT product distributions in hydrothermal systems include branched oxygenates.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis step 1: aminonitrile formation from isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mildly alkaline pH 8-9, concentrated evaporitic pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Classical Strecker mechanism: (1) Nucleophilic addition of NH\u2083 to the carbonyl of isobutyraldehyde forms a hemiaminal (carbinolamine). (2) Dehydration yields an imine (Schiff base), 2-methylpropan-1-imine. (3) Nucleophilic addition of HCN to the imine carbon yields \u03b1-aminoisovaleronitrile. Montmorillonite concentrates reactants on its surface and provides acid-base catalysis for each step.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker synthesis is one of the best-established prebiotic amino acid synthesis routes (Miller, 1957; Strecker, 1850). Isobutyraldehyde Strecker synthesis specifically produces valine precursors (Miller & Urey, 1959; Schlesinger & Miller, 1983). Montmorillonite clays catalyze Strecker reactions by concentrating reactants and providing acid-base sites (Ferris, 2005). The reaction proceeds efficiently under mild aqueous conditions with excess NH\u2083 and HCN.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis step 2: hydrolysis of aminonitrile to valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none (thermal/acid-catalyzed)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mildly acidic to neutral pH, prolonged aqueous conditions or heating\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acid-catalyzed hydrolysis of the nitrile group in \u03b1-aminoisovaleronitrile. The nitrile is first hydrated to an amide (\u03b1-aminoisovaleramide), then the amide undergoes further hydrolysis to yield the carboxylic acid (valine) with release of NH\u2083. Under prebiotic conditions, this occurs over extended time at ambient temperature or accelerated by mild heating.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis to carboxylic acids is spontaneous in aqueous solution, especially under mildly acidic conditions or elevated temperatures (Schlesinger & Miller, 1983). The hydrolysis of Strecker aminonitriles to amino acids was demonstrated in the original Miller-Urey experiments (Miller, 1957). The reaction is thermodynamically favorable (\u0394G < 0) and is accelerated at 350-370K, making geothermal pools ideal environments.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive carboxylation of acetaldehyde to pyruvate on native iron\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe\u2070)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-300 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"native iron (Fe\u2070)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mildly alkaline, CO\u2082 saturated fluid\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 fixation onto acetaldehyde via reductive carboxylation on native iron surface. Fe\u2070 provides electrons for the activation of CO\u2082. The activated CO\u2082 species attacks the carbonyl carbon of acetaldehyde, forming a C3 \u03b1-keto acid (pyruvate) through a mechanism analogous to enzymatic pyruvate synthase (CO\u2082 + 2e\u207b + acetaldehyde \u2192 pyruvate).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Varma et al. (2018, Nature Ecology & Evolution) demonstrated that native iron (Fe\u2070) promotes CO\u2082 fixation to generate \u03b1-keto acids including pyruvate from acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 under hydrothermal conditions. This is a key finding establishing a non-enzymatic analog of the reductive acetyl-CoA pathway and reductive TCA cycle reactions. Pyruvate yields of ~1-5% were observed at 100\u00b0C.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive carboxylation of isobutyraldehyde to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate on native iron\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe\u2070)\", \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-300 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"native iron (Fe\u2070) with greigite co-catalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mildly alkaline, CO\u2082 saturated, analogous to Varma et al. conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 fixation onto isobutyraldehyde via reductive carboxylation on native iron surface, directly analogous to pyruvate formation from acetaldehyde (rxn_012). Fe\u2070 activates CO\u2082, which attacks the carbonyl carbon of isobutyraldehyde, forming the C5 \u03b1-keto acid (\u03b1-ketoisovalerate). The branched chain of isobutyraldehyde is preserved in the product.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"By direct analogy with Varma et al. (2018), who showed Fe\u2070-mediated CO\u2082 fixation onto aldehydes to generate \u03b1-keto acids, isobutyraldehyde + CO\u2082 \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate is a logical extension. Muchowska et al. (2019, Nature) demonstrated that Fe\u2070 promotes a wide range of \u03b1-keto acid syntheses from aldehydes + CO\u2082, supporting the generality of this reductive carboxylation mechanism. This avoids the problematic acetolactate pathway entirely.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate to valine on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/FeS\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"NH\u2083-rich alkaline vent fluid, pH 9-11\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reductive amination on mineral surface: (1) NH\u2083 attacks the keto group of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate forming a carbinolamine. (2) Dehydration yields an imine (Schiff base). (3) Reduction of the C=N double bond by H\u2082 (or surface-bound hydride from FeS) yields valine. FeS/Fe\u2083S\u2084 surfaces facilitate all three steps.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003) demonstrated reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids on FeS/NiS surfaces under simulated hydrothermal conditions. Wang et al. (2005) showed that greigite and other iron sulfides promote reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine. By extension, \u03b1-ketoisovalerate undergoes analogous reductive amination to valine. The reaction is thermodynamically favorable under reducing hydrothermal conditions with excess NH\u2083.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"NH\u2083-rich alkaline vent fluid\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine: NH\u2083 attacks the keto carbonyl of pyruvate, dehydration gives pyruvate imine, and reduction on greigite surface yields alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003) demonstrated reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine on metal sulfide surfaces. Wang et al. (2005) confirmed this with greigite catalysis. Alanine is one of the most readily synthesized amino acids via reductive amination, providing the amino donor for subsequent transamination to valine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Transamination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate with alanine to form valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu\u00b2\u207a or Fe\u00b2\u207a ions as Lewis acid catalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrated pool, Cu\u00b2\u207a/Fe\u00b2\u207a ~1-10 mM, pH 5-8\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Metal-ion-catalyzed transamination. Cu\u00b2\u207a or Fe\u00b2\u207a coordinates both the amino group of alanine and the keto group of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, facilitating proton transfer and amino group exchange through a geminal diamine intermediate. Alanine donates its amino group to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, yielding valine and regenerating pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Meinert et al. (2016) and Transamination reactions have been shown to proceed abiotically in the presence of metal ions, especially Cu\u00b2\u207a (Crespo-Hernandez et al.). Nakada & Hagiwara (1966) demonstrated non-enzymatic transamination between amino acids and \u03b1-keto acids catalyzed by metal ions. Pyruvate regeneration creates a catalytic cycle, consistent with proto-metabolic network concepts (Smith & Morowitz, 2004). This provides a third independent route to valine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis of glycine from formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic pool, concentrated reactants\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Strecker synthesis using formaldehyde as the aldehyde: HCHO + NH\u2083 \u2192 methyleneamine, then + HCN \u2192 aminoacetonitrile, then hydrolysis \u2192 glycine. The simplest Strecker synthesis producing the simplest amino acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glycine is the most abundant amino acid in Miller-Urey experiments and the simplest Strecker product (Miller, 1957). Its synthesis from HCHO + HCN + NH\u2083 is the archetypal Strecker reaction and is exceptionally well-supported experimentally. Glycine serves as an alternative amino group donor for transamination reactions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Transamination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate with glycine to form valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu\u00b2\u207a or Fe\u00b2\u207a ions\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrated pool, metal ions present\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Metal-ion-catalyzed transamination between glycine (amino donor) and \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (keto acceptor). The glycine amino group is transferred to the keto position of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, producing valine and glyoxylate as the keto acid byproduct.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Analogous to rxn_016 but using glycine as the amino donor. Non-enzymatic transamination with glycine has been demonstrated under prebiotic conditions (Nakada & Hagiwara, 1966). Using glycine provides an alternative amino group source independent of the alanine/pyruvate cycle, increasing network robustness.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_019\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanohydrin formation from isobutyraldehyde with HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mildly basic pH favors CN\u207b nucleophile\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic addition of cyanide (CN\u207b) to the carbonyl carbon of isobutyraldehyde to form the cyanohydrin (2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile). The reaction proceeds under mild conditions in aqueous solution, favored at pH 8-9 where CN\u207b concentration is appreciable.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cyanohydrin formation is the first mechanistic step of the Strecker synthesis when performed without initial imine formation (Strecker, 1850). The cyanohydrin can proceed to valine via two distinct routes: (1) ammonolysis followed by hydrolysis (Strecker completion), or (2) hydrolysis to \u03b1-hydroxy acid then conversion to \u03b1-keto acid. This branching point increases pathway diversity.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_020\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanohydrin ammonolysis and hydrolysis to valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"330-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"prolonged heating in NH\u2083-rich solution, geothermal pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The cyanohydrin undergoes ammonolysis: NH\u2083 displaces the hydroxyl group at the alpha carbon to give \u03b1-aminoisovaleronitrile (mol_012 equivalent), followed by nitrile hydrolysis (nitrile \u2192 amide \u2192 carboxylic acid) to yield valine. The two-step process of SN2 ammonolysis + hydrolysis proceeds thermally in NH\u2083-rich geothermal pool conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The cyanohydrin-to-amino-acid route is a variant of the Strecker synthesis documented by Commeyras et al. (2002) and studied in the context of \u03b1-amino acid synthesis in prebiotic chemistry. In concentrated NH\u2083 solutions under mild heating, the hydroxyl group is displaced by NH\u2083, and subsequent hydrolysis converts the nitrile to the carboxylic acid. This provides an alternative to the direct imine-HCN Strecker route.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_021\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"340-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"clay surface / metal ions\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling concentrates pyruvate, thermal decarboxylation during dry phase\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate: CH\u2083COCOO\u207b \u2192 CH\u2083CHO + CO\u2082. The \u03b2-keto acid motif makes decarboxylation facile. Loss of CO\u2082 from the carboxylate group yields acetaldehyde. Metal ions (Fe\u00b2\u207a, Mn\u00b2\u207a) on clay surfaces lower the activation energy.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate decarboxylation is thermodynamically favorable and well-documented under prebiotic conditions (Cooper et al., 2011). Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate occurs readily at 60-100\u00b0C in aqueous solution (Sato & Itoh, 2006). This creates a bidirectional connection between pyruvate and acetaldehyde, enabling the pyruvate \u2194 acetaldehyde cycle that connects the transamination and FTT branches of the network.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Primary Strecker via aldol-derived isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"The strongest and best-supported pathway. Hydrothermal CO\u2082 \u2192 CO via magnetite, then FTT gives formaldehyde and propanal. Surface aldol condensation of propanal + formaldehyde \u2192 methacrolein \u2192 isobutyraldehyde. Strecker synthesis with HCN + NH\u2083 gives aminonitrile, hydrolysis yields valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker via formate-derived formaldehyde and FTT propanal\",\n      \"description\": \"Alternative formaldehyde source via greigite-catalyzed CO\u2082 \u2192 formate, then Fe\u2070 reduction to formaldehyde. Propanal from FTT. Aldol \u2192 isobutyraldehyde \u2192 Strecker \u2192 valine. Uses two independent hydrothermal C1 pathways.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker via direct FTT isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"Shortest pathway. Hydrothermal FTT directly produces branched isobutyraldehyde (low yield). Surface Strecker with HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 aminonitrile \u2192 valine. Only 4 reaction steps, minimal accumulated uncertainty per step but low initial yield.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination via aldol isobutyraldehyde carboxylation\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal CO\u2082 \u2192 CO \u2192 FTT aldehydes. Surface aldol gives isobutyraldehyde. Hydrothermal Fe\u2070-mediated carboxylation gives \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (Varma et al. analog). Reductive amination on greigite yields valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination via direct FTT isobutyraldehyde carboxylation\",\n      \"description\": \"FTT directly produces isobutyraldehyde. Fe\u2070-mediated carboxylation with CO\u2082 gives \u03b1-ketoisovalerate. Reductive amination on greigite yields valine. Short pathway, 4 steps.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Transamination with alanine via aldol route\",\n      \"description\": \"Convergent pathway requiring both \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (from aldol-derived isobutyraldehyde + CO\u2082 carboxylation) and alanine (from FTT acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate \u2192 reductive amination). Transamination yields valine and regenerates pyruvate in a catalytic cycle.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Transamination with glycine\",\n      \"description\": \"\u03b1-Ketoisovalerate from any route (P4/P5) combined with glycine from Strecker synthesis of formaldehyde. Transamination yields valine. Uses glycine as alternative amino donor independent of pyruvate/alanine cycle.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanohydrin route to valine\",\n      \"description\": \"Isobutyraldehyde (from aldol or FTT) reacts with HCN to form cyanohydrin intermediate. Subsequent ammonolysis and hydrolysis yields valine. Mechanistic variant of Strecker that proceeds through a distinct cyanohydrin intermediate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_019\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate-formaldehyde-HCN integrated Strecker with FTT isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"Uses the formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 HCN branch for cyanide source, combined with direct FTT isobutyraldehyde. Integrates both hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation pathways into a single route to valine via Strecker.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate decarboxylation recycling with transamination\",\n      \"description\": \"Demonstrates the full proto-metabolic cycle. FTT acetaldehyde \u2192 pyruvate (Fe\u2070 carboxylation) \u2192 alanine (reductive amination). Separately, pyruvate decarboxylation regenerates acetaldehyde. \u03b1-Ketoisovalerate from FTT isobutyraldehyde carboxylation. Transamination of \u03b1-KIV + alanine \u2192 valine + pyruvate, closing the cycle.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_021\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_014\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_013\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde - C1 hub produced by two independent hydrothermal routes (FTT from CO and formate reduction), consumed in HCN synthesis, aldol condensation with propanal, and glycine Strecker synthesis\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN - essential nitrogen-containing C1 building block produced from NH\u2083 + HCHO photochemistry, consumed in three Strecker-type reactions (valine aminonitrile, cyanohydrin, glycine)\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"description\": \"Isobutyraldehyde - critical C4 branched hub produced by two routes (aldol via methacrolein and direct FTT), consumed in Strecker aminonitrile, cyanohydrin formation, and reductive carboxylation to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"description\": \"\u03b1-Ketoisovalerate - penultimate hub produced by Fe\u2070-mediated carboxylation of isobutyraldehyde, consumed in three terminal valine-forming reactions (reductive amination, transamination with alanine, transamination with glycine)\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate - central metabolic hub produced by Fe\u2070 carboxylation of acetaldehyde and regenerated by transamination. Connected to alanine synthesis, acetaldehyde recycling via decarboxylation, and the transamination cycle.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_015\", \"rxn_021\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Valine", "overall_strategy": "This network generates valine through three independent terminal routes\u2014Strecker synthesis, reductive amination, and transamination\u2014all converging from prebiotically plausible C1-C4 building blocks. The strategy avoids the speculative acetolactate pathway entirely, instead using Varma et al.-type reductive carboxylation of isobutyraldehyde to generate \u03b1-ketoisovalerate. Hydrothermal environments produce C1 species (CO, formate, formaldehyde) and small aldehydes (acetaldehyde, propanal) via Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry on mineral catalysts. Surface environments drive aldol condensation, HCN synthesis, and Strecker chemistry. Biochemical environments enable transamination and final macromolecular-level assembly. Hub molecules (formaldehyde, HCN, isobutyraldehyde, \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, pyruvate) create genuine convergence points where multiple independent routes intersect, providing redundancy and robustness.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "dihydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen gas", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "ammonia", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "water", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CO", "iupac_name": "carbon monoxide", "common_name": "carbon monoxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO/c1-2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CHOO-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "acetaldehyde", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C3H6O", "iupac_name": "propanal", "common_name": "propanal", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O/c1-2-3-4/h3H,2H2,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C4H8O", "iupac_name": "2-methylpropanal", "common_name": "isobutyraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8O/c1-3(2)4-5/h3-4H,1-2H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C5H10N2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile", "common_name": "alpha-aminoisovaleronitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H10N2/c1-3(2)4(6)5-7/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C3H3O3-", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoate", "common_name": "pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)/p-1", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C5H7O3-", "iupac_name": "3-methyl-2-oxobutanoate", "common_name": "alpha-ketoisovalerate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H8O3/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)/p-1", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C4H6O", "iupac_name": "2-methylprop-2-enal", "common_name": "methacrolein", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6O/c1-3(2)4-5/h4H,1H2,2H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C5H11NO2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid", "common_name": "valine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H11NO2/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C2H5NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminoacetic acid", "common_name": "glycine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C4H7NO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile", "common_name": "isobutyraldehyde cyanohydrin", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO/c1-3(2)4(6)5-7/h3-4,6H,1-2H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "CO\u2082 reduction to CO via reverse water-gas shift on magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005", "mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (100-400 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "serpentinization-derived H\u2082"}, "mechanism": "Reverse water-gas shift reaction: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 CO + H\u2082O catalyzed on magnetite surfaces at hydrothermal temperatures. CO\u2082 adsorbs on Fe\u00b3\u207a sites and is reduced by H\u2082 dissociated on the mineral surface.", "reasoning": "Magnetite-catalyzed reverse water-gas shift is well-established in hydrothermal experiments. Seewald et al. (2006) demonstrated CO\u2082-CO interconversion under hydrothermal conditions. Magnetite is a known catalyst for this reaction at 400-500K (McCollom & Seewald, 2007). CO is a critical C1 feedstock for subsequent Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "CO\u2082 reduction to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (100-300 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 is adsorbed onto the greigite surface, which acts as an analog of biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters. Hydride transfer from surface-bound H\u2082 reduces CO\u2082 to formate (HCOO\u207b) via a two-electron reduction.", "reasoning": "Roldan et al. (2015) demonstrated that greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084) reduces CO\u2082 to formate under mild hydrothermal conditions, drawing the analogy between greigite and the [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters in carbon-fixing enzymes like CO dehydrogenase/acetyl-CoA synthase. Herschy et al. (2014) confirmed formate production in simulated alkaline vent conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type formaldehyde synthesis from CO", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (100-400 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "FTT synthesis regime, CO:H\u2082 \u2248 1:2"}, "mechanism": "CO hydrogenation on magnetite surface via Fischer-Tropsch-type mechanism. CO adsorbs on iron surface, H\u2082 dissociates, and stepwise hydrogenation yields formaldehyde (the C1 oxygenate product). Partial hydrogenation is favored at lower residence times.", "reasoning": "McCollom et al. (1999) and McCollom & Seewald (2006) demonstrated FTT synthesis of small oxygenates including formaldehyde on magnetite surfaces under hydrothermal conditions. Formaldehyde is the simplest aldehyde product and serves as a C1 building block for subsequent aldol chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Formate reduction to formaldehyde on native iron", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe\u2070)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (100-300 bar)", "catalyst": "elemental iron (Fe\u2070)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mildly alkaline, reducing conditions"}, "mechanism": "Two-electron reduction of formate on native iron surface. Fe\u2070 acts as electron donor, reducing the carboxylate group of formate to the aldehyde oxidation state, yielding formaldehyde. Fe\u2070 is oxidized to Fe\u00b2\u207a.", "reasoning": "Varma et al. (2018) showed that native iron (Fe\u2070) in aqueous conditions acts as a potent reductant capable of multi-electron reductions of C1 species. The reduction of formate to formaldehyde is thermodynamically favorable with Fe\u2070 as reductant under mildly alkaline hydrothermal conditions. This provides an alternative formaldehyde source independent of CO-based FTT."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of C2-C3 aldehydes", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009", "mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "420-500K", "pressure": "high (200-500 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "FTT regime with chain growth, Anderson-Schulz-Flory distribution"}, "mechanism": "Fischer-Tropsch-type chain growth on magnetite surface. CO and H\u2082 undergo repeated C1 insertion and hydrogenation steps. Chain termination via oxygenate pathway yields linear aldehydes: acetaldehyde (C2) and propanal (C3) as products following Anderson-Schulz-Flory distribution.", "reasoning": "McCollom et al. (1999) demonstrated FTT synthesis of linear C1-C5 oxygenates (alcohols, aldehydes) on magnetite catalysts under hydrothermal conditions. Acetaldehyde and propanal are well-established FTT products with reasonable yields. Rushdi & Simoneit (2001) confirmed the formation of C2-C4 oxygenates in FTT experiments."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Photochemical HCN synthesis from NH\u2083 and formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO\u2082 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO\u2082 (anatase)", "aqueous": "false", "other": "UV irradiation (\u03bb < 300 nm), no ozone layer, gas-phase or thin film"}, "mechanism": "UV photolysis of formaldehyde generates radical intermediates. TiO\u2082 photocatalysis generates reactive oxygen species and surface radicals. Ammonia reacts with formaldehyde-derived radicals (\u00b7CHO, \u00b7CH\u2082OH) on TiO\u2082 surface to form aminomethanol, which dehydrates to formaldimine (CH\u2082=NH), then further dehydrogenation under UV yields HCN.", "reasoning": "Ferris & Hagan (1984) demonstrated HCN production from NH\u2083 and CH\u2082O under UV irradiation. TiO\u2082 photocatalysis enhances this reaction (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012). HCN is also produced volcanically, but this synthetic route from prebiotically available HCHO and NH\u2083 ensures the network is self-contained. HCN is essential for Strecker synthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Cross-aldol condensation of propanal with formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mildly alkaline pH 8-10, wet-dry cycling promotes concentration"}, "mechanism": "Base-catalyzed cross-aldol condensation. The alpha-proton of propanal is abstracted by basic sites on montmorillonite. The resulting enolate attacks the carbonyl of formaldehyde to give 2-(hydroxymethyl)propanal. Subsequent dehydration (promoted by dry phase of wet-dry cycle) yields methacrolein (2-methylprop-2-enal).", "reasoning": "Aldol condensations between small aldehydes are well-established in prebiotic chemistry. Weber (1992, 2001) demonstrated sugar synthesis via aldol reactions under prebiotic conditions. Montmorillonite catalyzes aldol reactions through its Br\u00f8nsted acid/base sites and concentrates organics via adsorption (Ferris, 2005). Cross-aldol of propanal with formaldehyde is thermodynamically favored because formaldehyde has no alpha-H and acts exclusively as the electrophile."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Reduction of methacrolein to isobutyraldehyde on pyrite", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS\u2082)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "pyrite/mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "FeS as electron donor, mildly acidic to neutral pH"}, "mechanism": "Selective hydrogenation of the C=C double bond in methacrolein while preserving the aldehyde group. FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces donate electrons for the reduction. H\u2082 dissociates on pyrite surface providing H atoms for 1,4-conjugate addition across the \u03b1,\u03b2-unsaturated aldehyde system, yielding the saturated isobutyraldehyde.", "reasoning": "Pyrite and mackinawite surfaces are known to catalyze reductions of organic molecules. W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1988, 1992) proposed FeS/FeS\u2082 as primordial reducing agents. Cody et al. (2004) demonstrated that metal sulfide surfaces can selectively reduce unsaturated organic compounds. The selective 1,4-reduction of an \u03b1,\u03b2-unsaturated aldehyde to a saturated aldehyde is thermodynamically favorable and well-established in heterogeneous catalysis."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Direct FTT synthesis of isobutyraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "elemental iron (Fe\u2070)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "450-550K", "pressure": "high (200-500 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite with Fe\u2070 co-catalyst", "aqueous": "true", "other": "FTT conditions favoring branching, higher temperature regime"}, "mechanism": "Fischer-Tropsch-type chain growth with branch formation. At higher temperatures, secondary carbon radical intermediates on the catalyst surface undergo \u03b2-hydride elimination and re-insertion, creating branched products. Chain termination by CO insertion and hydrogenation at the branch point yields 2-methylpropanal (isobutyraldehyde) as a minor branched C4 product.", "reasoning": "While FTT primarily yields linear products following Anderson-Schulz-Flory distribution, branched products including isobutyraldehyde have been detected in FTT experiments at elevated temperatures (Rushdi & Simoneit, 2001). The branching fraction increases with temperature. Yields are low (typically <5% of C4 fraction is branched), but this provides an alternative hydrothermal route to isobutyraldehyde independent of the aldol pathway. McCollom & Seewald (2007) note that FTT product distributions in hydrothermal systems include branched oxygenates."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Strecker synthesis step 1: aminonitrile formation from isobutyraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_008", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mildly alkaline pH 8-9, concentrated evaporitic pool"}, "mechanism": "Classical Strecker mechanism: (1) Nucleophilic addition of NH\u2083 to the carbonyl of isobutyraldehyde forms a hemiaminal (carbinolamine). (2) Dehydration yields an imine (Schiff base), 2-methylpropan-1-imine. (3) Nucleophilic addition of HCN to the imine carbon yields \u03b1-aminoisovaleronitrile. Montmorillonite concentrates reactants on its surface and provides acid-base catalysis for each step.", "reasoning": "The Strecker synthesis is one of the best-established prebiotic amino acid synthesis routes (Miller, 1957; Strecker, 1850). Isobutyraldehyde Strecker synthesis specifically produces valine precursors (Miller & Urey, 1959; Schlesinger & Miller, 1983). Montmorillonite clays catalyze Strecker reactions by concentrating reactants and providing acid-base sites (Ferris, 2005). The reaction proceeds efficiently under mild aqueous conditions with excess NH\u2083 and HCN."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Strecker synthesis step 2: hydrolysis of aminonitrile to valine", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none (thermal/acid-catalyzed)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mildly acidic to neutral pH, prolonged aqueous conditions or heating"}, "mechanism": "Acid-catalyzed hydrolysis of the nitrile group in \u03b1-aminoisovaleronitrile. The nitrile is first hydrated to an amide (\u03b1-aminoisovaleramide), then the amide undergoes further hydrolysis to yield the carboxylic acid (valine) with release of NH\u2083. Under prebiotic conditions, this occurs over extended time at ambient temperature or accelerated by mild heating.", "reasoning": "Nitrile hydrolysis to carboxylic acids is spontaneous in aqueous solution, especially under mildly acidic conditions or elevated temperatures (Schlesinger & Miller, 1983). The hydrolysis of Strecker aminonitriles to amino acids was demonstrated in the original Miller-Urey experiments (Miller, 1957). The reaction is thermodynamically favorable (\u0394G < 0) and is accelerated at 350-370K, making geothermal pools ideal environments."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Reductive carboxylation of acetaldehyde to pyruvate on native iron", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe\u2070)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (100-300 bar)", "catalyst": "native iron (Fe\u2070)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mildly alkaline, CO\u2082 saturated fluid"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 fixation onto acetaldehyde via reductive carboxylation on native iron surface. Fe\u2070 provides electrons for the activation of CO\u2082. The activated CO\u2082 species attacks the carbonyl carbon of acetaldehyde, forming a C3 \u03b1-keto acid (pyruvate) through a mechanism analogous to enzymatic pyruvate synthase (CO\u2082 + 2e\u207b + acetaldehyde \u2192 pyruvate).", "reasoning": "Varma et al. (2018, Nature Ecology & Evolution) demonstrated that native iron (Fe\u2070) promotes CO\u2082 fixation to generate \u03b1-keto acids including pyruvate from acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 under hydrothermal conditions. This is a key finding establishing a non-enzymatic analog of the reductive acetyl-CoA pathway and reductive TCA cycle reactions. Pyruvate yields of ~1-5% were observed at 100\u00b0C."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Reductive carboxylation of isobutyraldehyde to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate on native iron", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe\u2070)", "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (100-300 bar)", "catalyst": "native iron (Fe\u2070) with greigite co-catalyst", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mildly alkaline, CO\u2082 saturated, analogous to Varma et al. conditions"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 fixation onto isobutyraldehyde via reductive carboxylation on native iron surface, directly analogous to pyruvate formation from acetaldehyde (rxn_012). Fe\u2070 activates CO\u2082, which attacks the carbonyl carbon of isobutyraldehyde, forming the C5 \u03b1-keto acid (\u03b1-ketoisovalerate). The branched chain of isobutyraldehyde is preserved in the product.", "reasoning": "By direct analogy with Varma et al. (2018), who showed Fe\u2070-mediated CO\u2082 fixation onto aldehydes to generate \u03b1-keto acids, isobutyraldehyde + CO\u2082 \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate is a logical extension. Muchowska et al. (2019, Nature) demonstrated that Fe\u2070 promotes a wide range of \u03b1-keto acid syntheses from aldehydes + CO\u2082, supporting the generality of this reductive carboxylation mechanism. This avoids the problematic acetolactate pathway entirely."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate to valine on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite/FeS", "aqueous": "true", "other": "NH\u2083-rich alkaline vent fluid, pH 9-11"}, "mechanism": "Reductive amination on mineral surface: (1) NH\u2083 attacks the keto group of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate forming a carbinolamine. (2) Dehydration yields an imine (Schiff base). (3) Reduction of the C=N double bond by H\u2082 (or surface-bound hydride from FeS) yields valine. FeS/Fe\u2083S\u2084 surfaces facilitate all three steps.", "reasoning": "Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003) demonstrated reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids on FeS/NiS surfaces under simulated hydrothermal conditions. Wang et al. (2005) showed that greigite and other iron sulfides promote reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine. By extension, \u03b1-ketoisovalerate undergoes analogous reductive amination to valine. The reaction is thermodynamically favorable under reducing hydrothermal conditions with excess NH\u2083."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "NH\u2083-rich alkaline vent fluid"}, "mechanism": "Reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine: NH\u2083 attacks the keto carbonyl of pyruvate, dehydration gives pyruvate imine, and reduction on greigite surface yields alanine.", "reasoning": "Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003) demonstrated reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine on metal sulfide surfaces. Wang et al. (2005) confirmed this with greigite catalysis. Alanine is one of the most readily synthesized amino acids via reductive amination, providing the amino donor for subsequent transamination to valine."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Transamination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate with alanine to form valine", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_017", "mol_013"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu\u00b2\u207a or Fe\u00b2\u207a ions as Lewis acid catalyst", "aqueous": "true", "other": "concentrated pool, Cu\u00b2\u207a/Fe\u00b2\u207a ~1-10 mM, pH 5-8"}, "mechanism": "Metal-ion-catalyzed transamination. Cu\u00b2\u207a or Fe\u00b2\u207a coordinates both the amino group of alanine and the keto group of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, facilitating proton transfer and amino group exchange through a geminal diamine intermediate. Alanine donates its amino group to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, yielding valine and regenerating pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Meinert et al. (2016) and Transamination reactions have been shown to proceed abiotically in the presence of metal ions, especially Cu\u00b2\u207a (Crespo-Hernandez et al.). Nakada & Hagiwara (1966) demonstrated non-enzymatic transamination between amino acids and \u03b1-keto acids catalyzed by metal ions. Pyruvate regeneration creates a catalytic cycle, consistent with proto-metabolic network concepts (Smith & Morowitz, 2004). This provides a third independent route to valine."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Strecker synthesis of glycine from formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pool, concentrated reactants"}, "mechanism": "Strecker synthesis using formaldehyde as the aldehyde: HCHO + NH\u2083 \u2192 methyleneamine, then + HCN \u2192 aminoacetonitrile, then hydrolysis \u2192 glycine. The simplest Strecker synthesis producing the simplest amino acid.", "reasoning": "Glycine is the most abundant amino acid in Miller-Urey experiments and the simplest Strecker product (Miller, 1957). Its synthesis from HCHO + HCN + NH\u2083 is the archetypal Strecker reaction and is exceptionally well-supported experimentally. Glycine serves as an alternative amino group donor for transamination reactions."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Transamination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate with glycine to form valine", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_018"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu\u00b2\u207a or Fe\u00b2\u207a ions", "aqueous": "true", "other": "concentrated pool, metal ions present"}, "mechanism": "Metal-ion-catalyzed transamination between glycine (amino donor) and \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (keto acceptor). The glycine amino group is transferred to the keto position of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, producing valine and glyoxylate as the keto acid byproduct.", "reasoning": "Analogous to rxn_016 but using glycine as the amino donor. Non-enzymatic transamination with glycine has been demonstrated under prebiotic conditions (Nakada & Hagiwara, 1966). Using glycine provides an alternative amino group source independent of the alanine/pyruvate cycle, increasing network robustness."}, {"id": "rxn_019", "name": "Cyanohydrin formation from isobutyraldehyde with HCN", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mildly basic pH favors CN\u207b nucleophile"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic addition of cyanide (CN\u207b) to the carbonyl carbon of isobutyraldehyde to form the cyanohydrin (2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile). The reaction proceeds under mild conditions in aqueous solution, favored at pH 8-9 where CN\u207b concentration is appreciable.", "reasoning": "Cyanohydrin formation is the first mechanistic step of the Strecker synthesis when performed without initial imine formation (Strecker, 1850). The cyanohydrin can proceed to valine via two distinct routes: (1) ammonolysis followed by hydrolysis (Strecker completion), or (2) hydrolysis to \u03b1-hydroxy acid then conversion to \u03b1-keto acid. This branching point increases pathway diversity."}, {"id": "rxn_020", "name": "Cyanohydrin ammonolysis and hydrolysis to valine", "inputs": ["mol_019", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "330-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none", "aqueous": "true", "other": "prolonged heating in NH\u2083-rich solution, geothermal pool"}, "mechanism": "The cyanohydrin undergoes ammonolysis: NH\u2083 displaces the hydroxyl group at the alpha carbon to give \u03b1-aminoisovaleronitrile (mol_012 equivalent), followed by nitrile hydrolysis (nitrile \u2192 amide \u2192 carboxylic acid) to yield valine. The two-step process of SN2 ammonolysis + hydrolysis proceeds thermally in NH\u2083-rich geothermal pool conditions.", "reasoning": "The cyanohydrin-to-amino-acid route is a variant of the Strecker synthesis documented by Commeyras et al. (2002) and studied in the context of \u03b1-amino acid synthesis in prebiotic chemistry. In concentrated NH\u2083 solutions under mild heating, the hydroxyl group is displaced by NH\u2083, and subsequent hydrolysis converts the nitrile to the carboxylic acid. This provides an alternative to the direct imine-HCN Strecker route."}, {"id": "rxn_021", "name": "Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_009", "mol_001"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "340-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "clay surface / metal ions", "aqueous": "true", "other": "wet-dry cycling concentrates pyruvate, thermal decarboxylation during dry phase"}, "mechanism": "Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate: CH\u2083COCOO\u207b \u2192 CH\u2083CHO + CO\u2082. The \u03b2-keto acid motif makes decarboxylation facile. Loss of CO\u2082 from the carboxylate group yields acetaldehyde. Metal ions (Fe\u00b2\u207a, Mn\u00b2\u207a) on clay surfaces lower the activation energy.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate decarboxylation is thermodynamically favorable and well-documented under prebiotic conditions (Cooper et al., 2011). Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate occurs readily at 60-100\u00b0C in aqueous solution (Sato & Itoh, 2006). This creates a bidirectional connection between pyruvate and acetaldehyde, enabling the pyruvate \u2194 acetaldehyde cycle that connects the transamination and FTT branches of the network."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Primary Strecker via aldol-derived isobutyraldehyde", "description": "The strongest and best-supported pathway. Hydrothermal CO\u2082 \u2192 CO via magnetite, then FTT gives formaldehyde and propanal. Surface aldol condensation of propanal + formaldehyde \u2192 methacrolein \u2192 isobutyraldehyde. Strecker synthesis with HCN + NH\u2083 gives aminonitrile, hydrolysis yields valine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_007", "mol_010", "mol_016", "mol_011", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Strecker via formate-derived formaldehyde and FTT propanal", "description": "Alternative formaldehyde source via greigite-catalyzed CO\u2082 \u2192 formate, then Fe\u2070 reduction to formaldehyde. Propanal from FTT. Aldol \u2192 isobutyraldehyde \u2192 Strecker \u2192 valine. Uses two independent hydrothermal C1 pathways.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_001", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Strecker via direct FTT isobutyraldehyde", "description": "Shortest pathway. Hydrothermal FTT directly produces branched isobutyraldehyde (low yield). Surface Strecker with HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 aminonitrile \u2192 valine. Only 4 reaction steps, minimal accumulated uncertainty per step but low initial yield.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_009", "rxn_006", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_011", "mol_008", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Reductive amination via aldol isobutyraldehyde carboxylation", "description": "Hydrothermal CO\u2082 \u2192 CO \u2192 FTT aldehydes. Surface aldol gives isobutyraldehyde. Hydrothermal Fe\u2070-mediated carboxylation gives \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (Varma et al. analog). Reductive amination on greigite yields valine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_013", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_010", "mol_016", "mol_011", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Reductive amination via direct FTT isobutyraldehyde carboxylation", "description": "FTT directly produces isobutyraldehyde. Fe\u2070-mediated carboxylation with CO\u2082 gives \u03b1-ketoisovalerate. Reductive amination on greigite yields valine. Short pathway, 4 steps.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_009", "rxn_013", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_011", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Transamination with alanine via aldol route", "description": "Convergent pathway requiring both \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (from aldol-derived isobutyraldehyde + CO\u2082 carboxylation) and alanine (from FTT acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate \u2192 reductive amination). Transamination yields valine and regenerates pyruvate in a catalytic cycle.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_013", "rxn_012", "rxn_015", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_014", "mol_009", "mol_013", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Transamination with glycine", "description": "\u03b1-Ketoisovalerate from any route (P4/P5) combined with glycine from Strecker synthesis of formaldehyde. Transamination yields valine. Uses glycine as alternative amino donor independent of pyruvate/alanine cycle.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_009", "rxn_013", "rxn_003", "rxn_006", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_014", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_018"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Cyanohydrin route to valine", "description": "Isobutyraldehyde (from aldol or FTT) reacts with HCN to form cyanohydrin intermediate. Subsequent ammonolysis and hydrolysis yields valine. Mechanistic variant of Strecker that proceeds through a distinct cyanohydrin intermediate.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_006", "rxn_019", "rxn_020"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_016", "mol_011", "mol_008", "mol_019"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Formate-formaldehyde-HCN integrated Strecker with FTT isobutyraldehyde", "description": "Uses the formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 HCN branch for cyanide source, combined with direct FTT isobutyraldehyde. Integrates both hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation pathways into a single route to valine via Strecker.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_001", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_011", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Pyruvate decarboxylation recycling with transamination", "description": "Demonstrates the full proto-metabolic cycle. FTT acetaldehyde \u2192 pyruvate (Fe\u2070 carboxylation) \u2192 alanine (reductive amination). Separately, pyruvate decarboxylation regenerates acetaldehyde. \u03b1-Ketoisovalerate from FTT isobutyraldehyde carboxylation. Transamination of \u03b1-KIV + alanine \u2192 valine + pyruvate, closing the cycle.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_005", "rxn_012", "rxn_015", "rxn_021", "rxn_009", "rxn_013", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_013", "mol_015", "mol_011", "mol_014"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_011", "mol_014", "mol_013"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_007", "description": "Formaldehyde - C1 hub produced by two independent hydrothermal routes (FTT from CO and formate reduction), consumed in HCN synthesis, aldol condensation with propanal, and glycine Strecker synthesis", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_017"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_008", "description": "HCN - essential nitrogen-containing C1 building block produced from NH\u2083 + HCHO photochemistry, consumed in three Strecker-type reactions (valine aminonitrile, cyanohydrin, glycine)", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_006"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_010", "rxn_017", "rxn_019"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_011", "description": "Isobutyraldehyde - critical C4 branched hub produced by two routes (aldol via methacrolein and direct FTT), consumed in Strecker aminonitrile, cyanohydrin formation, and reductive carboxylation to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_010", "rxn_013", "rxn_019"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_014", "description": "\u03b1-Ketoisovalerate - penultimate hub produced by Fe\u2070-mediated carboxylation of isobutyraldehyde, consumed in three terminal valine-forming reactions (reductive amination, transamination with alanine, transamination with glycine)", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_013"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_014", "rxn_016", "rxn_018"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_013", "description": "Pyruvate - central metabolic hub produced by Fe\u2070 carboxylation of acetaldehyde and regenerated by transamination. Connected to alanine synthesis, acetaldehyde recycling via decarboxylation, and the transamination cycle.", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_012", "rxn_016"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_015", "rxn_021"]}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 447617.3241138458, "success": true, "error_message": null}
