e is the simplest amino acid and likely the most abundant prebiotically. However, the same cofactor problem applies to rxn_018. Additionally, this pathway combines three problematic reactions (rxn_006, rxn_009, rxn_018).\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Replace rxn_009 with aldol route\", \"Specify transamination catalyst\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.80,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.75,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.72,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.60,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.50,\n        \"rxn_019\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_020\": 0.45\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.62,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.68,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.78,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.65,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.65,\n      \"feedback\": \"The cyanohydrin route is mechanistically problematic. rxn_020 (cyanohydrin + NH\u2083 \u2192 amino acid) reverses the standard Strecker order: in the conventional mechanism, the amine attacks the aldehyde first to form an imine, then HCN adds. When cyanohydrin forms first, ammonolysis would need to displace the hydroxyl\u2014this is thermodynamically unfavorable and would more likely yield \u03b1-hydroxy acids (not amino acids) under hydrolysis.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_020\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Reconsider mechanism: cyanohydrin hydrolysis gives \u03b1-hydroxy acids, not amino acids\", \"Merge rxn_019+rxn_020 into the standard Strecker sequence (rxn_010+rxn_011) instead\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.68,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.50,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.45,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.80\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.67,\n    